WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.120
[Amit Varma]: At a time when many of the institutions around us are being eroded, there is one that still

00:00:11.120 --> 00:00:16.400
[Amit Varma]: commands respect, the Indian Armed Forces. At the time of independence, the British passed

00:00:16.400 --> 00:00:21.720
[Amit Varma]: on a professional army to both India and Pakistan. But while the influence of the army was seen

00:00:21.720 --> 00:00:26.880
[Amit Varma]: in Pakistani politics, it has remained unseen in Indian politics. And that's a damn good

00:00:26.880 --> 00:00:32.120
[Amit Varma]: thing. The military has played an outsized role in many postcolonial nations, many of

00:00:32.120 --> 00:00:37.800
[Amit Varma]: which have been plagued with coups and an erosion of democracy. Pakistan is both a case

00:00:37.800 --> 00:00:42.840
[Amit Varma]: in point and a cautionary tale. The Indian Armed Forces have steadfastly remained far

00:00:42.840 --> 00:00:47.820
[Amit Varma]: away from politics. And this is not just because of good luck, but a result of conscious decisions

00:00:47.820 --> 00:00:52.620
[Amit Varma]: taken by our leaders through the last century. And while it's a good thing that the army

00:00:52.620 --> 00:00:57.760
[Amit Varma]: has stayed above politics, it's not quite a good thing that politicians increasingly

00:00:57.760 --> 00:01:03.000
[Amit Varma]: invoke the army for rhetorical purposes these days. It is also not a good thing that our

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:07.600
[Amit Varma]: political classes tend to take the armed forces for granted. We are lucky to have the armed

00:01:07.600 --> 00:01:22.600
[Unknown]: forces that we do. Let's not mess it up. Welcome to the Scene and the Unseen, our weekly podcast

00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:25.960
[Amit Varma]: on economics, politics and behavioral science. Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:25.960 --> 00:01:29.960
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the Scene and the Unseen. In this episode, we'll be talking about the Indian

00:01:29.960 --> 00:01:35.720
[Amit Varma]: Armed Forces. And my guest is Lieutenant General Prakash Menon, who's the Director of the Strategic

00:01:35.720 --> 00:01:40.740
[Amit Varma]: Studies Program at the Takshashila Institution in Bengaluru. General Menon has been a guest

00:01:40.740 --> 00:01:44.560
[Amit Varma]: on the show before when we discussed nuclear strategy, a subject on which he's written

00:01:44.560 --> 00:01:50.920
[Amit Varma]: a superb book. Both that episode and his book will be linked from the show notes. But before

00:01:50.920 --> 00:01:59.120
[Amit Varma]: we begin our conversation, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:01:59.120 --> 00:02:04.440
[Amit Varma]: Are you one of those people who not only loves to read, but also wants to write better? If

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:08.360
[Amit Varma]: so, I might have something for you. For the last couple of months, I've been teaching

00:02:08.360 --> 00:02:14.660
[Amit Varma]: an online course called the Art of Clear Writing. Four webinars spread out over four Saturdays,

00:02:14.660 --> 00:02:19.760
[Amit Varma]: in which I share whatever I have learned about the craft and practice of writing over 25

00:02:19.760 --> 00:02:25.540
[Amit Varma]: years as a professional writer. The course also includes many writing exercises, discussions

00:02:25.540 --> 00:02:32.160
[Amit Varma]: on email and WhatsApp and an interactive workshop. It costs rupees 10,000 or $150. You can check

00:02:32.160 --> 00:02:37.960
[Amit Varma]: out the details at indiauncut.com slash clear writing. This link will be in the show notes.

00:02:37.960 --> 00:02:41.520
[Amit Varma]: If you want to bridge the gap between the thoughts in your head and the words on the

00:02:41.520 --> 00:02:46.720
[Amit Varma]: page, then the Art of Clear Writing might be just what you need. June batches begin

00:02:46.720 --> 00:02:57.080
[Amit Varma]: soon. So register now. indiauncut.com slash clear writing.

00:02:57.080 --> 00:03:05.200
[Amit Varma]: Before we start talking about the army, both in terms of historical context and the structural

00:03:05.200 --> 00:03:09.280
[Amit Varma]: issues that it faces and so on, tell me a little bit about yourself. Why did you join

00:03:09.280 --> 00:03:10.280
[Amit Varma]: the army?

00:03:10.280 --> 00:03:17.800
[Guest]: Well, I actually went to the National Defense Academy, but I did not first join the army.

00:03:17.800 --> 00:03:24.920
[Guest]: I actually was a naval cadet because I come from a merchant navy family and my father

00:03:24.920 --> 00:03:33.320
[Guest]: is from the 1940 batch of the Dufferin. And it was during my second term at the NDA that

00:03:33.320 --> 00:03:42.320
[Guest]: I read a book on Field Marshal Rommel by a person called Desmond Young and was motivated

00:03:42.320 --> 00:03:48.320
[Guest]: to join the army. So I took the decision by myself without consulting my father and he

00:03:48.320 --> 00:03:54.960
[Guest]: was upset about it and gave an application that I want to convert my service from the

00:03:54.960 --> 00:03:58.720
[Guest]: navy to the army. And it was the easiest thing to do because navy at that time was a very

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:05.440
[Guest]: small service. So it was difficult being becoming a naval cadet, but much easier moving from

00:04:05.440 --> 00:04:12.600
[Guest]: the navy to the army. So that is how I got into the army. So I went in as a naval cadet

00:04:12.600 --> 00:04:14.640
[Amit Varma]: came out as an army cadet.

00:04:14.640 --> 00:04:19.280
[Amit Varma]: And one of the things I've realized about other government services, for example, the

00:04:19.280 --> 00:04:23.400
[Amit Varma]: civil services, my father was an IAS officer once upon a time. And one of the things I've

00:04:23.400 --> 00:04:28.160
[Amit Varma]: kind of realized is that back in the day, people used to enter, say, the civil services

00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:32.600
[Amit Varma]: and so on, with a fair bit of idealism and, you know, wanting to serve the country and

00:04:32.600 --> 00:04:38.040
[Amit Varma]: so on and so forth. And, you know, that idealism has been eroded over the decades. And today,

00:04:38.040 --> 00:04:42.880
[Amit Varma]: when you talk about the civil services, there's a lot of cynicism, so to say. But in your

00:04:42.880 --> 00:04:48.680
[Amit Varma]: case, in the case of the army, I'm assuming because the army is insulated from, you know,

00:04:48.680 --> 00:04:54.320
[Amit Varma]: the regular corruptions of daily governance, I'm guessing that would not apply. Like, do

00:04:54.320 --> 00:04:59.440
[Amit Varma]: you feel there's been a change for why people join the army over the years or?

00:04:59.440 --> 00:05:06.320
[Guest]: Well, actually, if you want to draw a comparison, probably there has been a change. There's

00:05:06.320 --> 00:05:16.240
[Guest]: no doubt because of the changes in the socioeconomic contours of this country itself. And therefore,

00:05:16.240 --> 00:05:22.200
[Guest]: the background from which people join the army are probably different from what they

00:05:22.200 --> 00:05:30.000
[Guest]: used to be in the old days. So there has been a change, no doubt. But I think as an institution,

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:39.480
[Guest]: the army, once you join it, has got that capacity to keep you motivated and actually bring out

00:05:39.480 --> 00:05:46.200
[Guest]: the best in you. Because I think that is the institutional capacity because we are based

00:05:46.200 --> 00:05:52.000
[Guest]: on what we call, and I belong to a fighting arm, I am an infantry officer, it is more

00:05:52.000 --> 00:06:01.560
[Guest]: pertinent that we are kept in such a state of, you can say, motivation that the larger

00:06:01.560 --> 00:06:08.680
[Guest]: and the outside world was at that time much more restricted to you. But that is not the

00:06:08.680 --> 00:06:16.360
[Guest]: case now because we never had the social media, we never had so much of press, we never had

00:06:16.360 --> 00:06:24.800
[Guest]: that much of exposure. So we've really lived in a very confined space. And surely the officer

00:06:24.800 --> 00:06:31.600
[Guest]: of today does not live in that same space. He lives in a space where he's exposed to

00:06:31.600 --> 00:06:42.400
[Guest]: the daily meanderings of India's politics, the world politics for that matter. And therefore,

00:06:42.400 --> 00:06:48.280
[Guest]: that exposure itself would have some sort of an influence. But I think the Indian Army

00:06:48.280 --> 00:06:55.880
[Guest]: still has that institutional capacity to make sure that the officer is still motivated and

00:06:55.880 --> 00:06:58.200
[Guest]: directed to the right space.

00:06:58.200 --> 00:07:02.880
[Amit Varma]: And is there also a sense that within the army, once you're part of the army, and not

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:07.280
[Amit Varma]: just if you're part of the army, but for your family itself, if you have a family member

00:07:07.280 --> 00:07:11.640
[Amit Varma]: in the army, like if you're growing up as an army kid, so to say, as the phrase goes,

00:07:11.640 --> 00:07:15.880
[Amit Varma]: that there is a sort of a separate culture of its own, which is homogenous through the

00:07:15.880 --> 00:07:20.280
[Amit Varma]: country and which kind of influences how people within the army look at each other and which

00:07:20.280 --> 00:07:25.800
[Amit Varma]: also insulates themselves from the larger sort of social currents around them.

00:07:25.800 --> 00:07:30.960
[Guest]: You know, obviously, it has a different value system, which is different from obviously

00:07:30.960 --> 00:07:39.460
[Guest]: the civilian space. But I think we must understand that the soldiers and your leadership come

00:07:39.460 --> 00:07:45.920
[Guest]: from the same society. And therefore, they can't purely be divorced from it. And what

00:07:45.920 --> 00:07:55.520
[Guest]: I found, at least, as India's economic growth took place, and as market forces sort of enveloped

00:07:55.520 --> 00:08:02.560
[Guest]: daily life, the value system itself also had to be affected by it. It could not be insulated

00:08:02.560 --> 00:08:03.560
[Guest]: from it.

00:08:03.560 --> 00:08:10.320
[Guest]: The question always was for the military leadership, that how does it adjust to these changes while

00:08:10.320 --> 00:08:19.800
[Guest]: it assimilates it without making sure that your military effectiveness is not impacted?

00:08:19.800 --> 00:08:24.600
[Guest]: That was a challenge of military leadership. It will continue to be the challenge of military

00:08:24.600 --> 00:08:30.440
[Guest]: leadership. Changes are, in fact, today, much more rapid than was it before. It will continue

00:08:30.440 --> 00:08:35.160
[Guest]: to impact. The question is, does the military leadership recognize how those changes are

00:08:35.160 --> 00:08:41.200
[Guest]: to be dealt with? And that becomes, I think, in today's world, much more challenging than

00:08:41.200 --> 00:08:43.840
[Guest]: it ever was before.

00:08:43.840 --> 00:08:47.880
[Amit Varma]: And you're one of the only two ex-army people who've come on my show, the other, of course,

00:08:47.880 --> 00:08:53.340
[Amit Varma]: being the historian Srinath Raghavan. And so, you know, I have selection bias here.

00:08:53.340 --> 00:08:57.760
[Amit Varma]: But within the army, you were an intellectual in the sense that, you know, you've written

00:08:57.760 --> 00:09:01.920
[Amit Varma]: a book on nuclear strategy and so on, and you've thought very deeply. Is there a tradition

00:09:01.920 --> 00:09:07.320
[Amit Varma]: of that within the army, within the officer class, so to say, or were you always an outlier

00:09:07.320 --> 00:09:11.600
[Amit Varma]: and an exception? And what's the culture like there in that sense?

00:09:11.600 --> 00:09:19.800
[Guest]: Well, I would say that at least in the early part of your upbringing, when you were actually

00:09:19.800 --> 00:09:27.600
[Guest]: more closer, more combat soldiering, which you do, there is really no time and no space

00:09:27.600 --> 00:09:33.720
[Guest]: for the type of intellectual activity, which you can probably indulge in after you've finished

00:09:33.720 --> 00:09:39.560
[Guest]: your active combat life. And which means that you are a colonel, which means you finish

00:09:39.560 --> 00:09:45.560
[Guest]: command of a unit. Then, of course, that experience, you can actually move in that space. And I

00:09:45.560 --> 00:09:53.560
[Guest]: think there are not all, but there are quite a lot of people actually who, because of their,

00:09:53.560 --> 00:09:59.480
[Guest]: and this is all up to the officer themselves. The institution actually gives you the opportunity,

00:09:59.480 --> 00:10:04.040
[Guest]: but it's entirely up to the officers, whether you want to, how much you want to read, how

00:10:04.040 --> 00:10:09.960
[Guest]: much you want to write about, how much you actually want to project and develop the idea.

00:10:09.960 --> 00:10:18.840
[Guest]: So my particular path was driven by the fact that in 1998, India went nuclear. I was that

00:10:18.840 --> 00:10:24.000
[Guest]: time a colonel, and I was interested to find out what meant for the armed forces and what

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:30.160
[Guest]: sort of, how does the role of the armed forces change because we are now a nuclear power.

00:10:30.160 --> 00:10:34.960
[Guest]: That drove me because my thoughts were actually not in consonance with the views, which are

00:10:34.960 --> 00:10:40.520
[Guest]: my peers and the seniors, which I had drawn. And I decided that I must find out. So that

00:10:40.520 --> 00:10:48.120
[Guest]: is why I therefore took study leave. I did my doctorate, finally converted that into

00:10:48.120 --> 00:10:52.640
[Guest]: a book and that's how my journey was lost. So I think it's an individual journey and

00:10:52.640 --> 00:10:54.280
[Guest]: there are a lot of people like that.

00:10:54.280 --> 00:10:59.400
[Amit Varma]: To sort of get back to history, you know, we often think of the Indian army as something

00:10:59.400 --> 00:11:03.640
[Amit Varma]: that we inherited from the British and we just carried on as we were, which of course

00:11:03.640 --> 00:11:10.320
[Amit Varma]: raises the extremely big question of why is it that essentially both India and Pakistan

00:11:10.320 --> 00:11:15.360
[Amit Varma]: inherited essentially the similar army, similar officers trained in exactly the same way.

00:11:15.360 --> 00:11:19.360
[Amit Varma]: But Pakistan, of course, has been beset with military dictatorships and the military has

00:11:19.360 --> 00:11:24.840
[Amit Varma]: always been a part of their politics. And we've completely escaped that. And one interesting

00:11:24.840 --> 00:11:29.200
[Amit Varma]: fact which I hadn't thought about before, which I got from Stephen Wilkinson's book

00:11:29.200 --> 00:11:33.520
[Amit Varma]: on the Indian army, which will be linked from the show notes, is about how the British army

00:11:33.520 --> 00:11:39.160
[Amit Varma]: was specifically set up for a very different purpose and what the post-colonial armies

00:11:39.160 --> 00:11:42.560
[Amit Varma]: would have to do. The purpose of the Indian and the Pakistani armies, of course, would

00:11:42.560 --> 00:11:47.400
[Amit Varma]: be to defend the borders and so on. You're defending the nation against external threats.

00:11:47.400 --> 00:11:52.360
[Amit Varma]: Whereas the whole point of the British army was to control the native population. And

00:11:52.360 --> 00:11:56.600
[Amit Varma]: to this effect, they carried out what is famously known as a divide and rule policy, which applied

00:11:56.600 --> 00:12:01.280
[Amit Varma]: to the army in the sense that they constructed a colonial Indian army. To quote Wilkinson,

00:12:01.280 --> 00:12:05.920
[Amit Varma]: quote, the colonial Indian army was deliberately constructed both to maximize its fighting

00:12:05.920 --> 00:12:10.760
[Amit Varma]: potential and to hedge against the threat of any repeat of a mutiny like that had almost

00:12:10.760 --> 00:12:16.440
[Amit Varma]: ended British control in 1857. Stop quote. And what they did was they recruited within

00:12:16.440 --> 00:12:21.520
[Amit Varma]: the army from what they considered the martial races. So there were many more Punjabis and

00:12:21.520 --> 00:12:28.280
[Amit Varma]: Pashtuns and there was a heavy imbalance that way. And what happened after sort of colonization

00:12:28.280 --> 00:12:33.000
[Amit Varma]: ended across the world was that in many countries, because it followed this kind of policy, you

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:38.960
[Amit Varma]: invariably had clashes between the army, which was controlled by minority interests against

00:12:38.960 --> 00:12:44.400
[Amit Varma]: the majority democratic forces at large, ending in many cases as we've seen with Pakistan.

00:12:44.400 --> 00:12:48.040
[Amit Varma]: But in India, it didn't happen. You know, Nehru famously wrote to his defense minister

00:12:48.040 --> 00:12:53.040
[Amit Varma]: in 46 or 47, where he said that this is something we must specifically watch out for. The Congress

00:12:53.040 --> 00:12:57.600
[Amit Varma]: had been thinking about it for more than 20 years. And B. R. Ambedkar had written a book

00:12:57.600 --> 00:13:02.920
[Amit Varma]: in 1941 called Thoughts on Pakistan, where he predicted that it was because of this compositional

00:13:02.920 --> 00:13:07.080
[Amit Varma]: makeup that, you know, Pakistan would have trouble with this army. And we were actually

00:13:07.080 --> 00:13:12.880
[Amit Varma]: better off letting Pakistan form because what would happen is we would get rid of a lot

00:13:12.880 --> 00:13:15.960
[Amit Varma]: of these problems. How did that play out? Can you tell me a little bit about how the

00:13:15.960 --> 00:13:16.960
[Guest]: army?

00:13:16.960 --> 00:13:21.640
[Guest]: See, actually, if you look at the army, don't forget that the army was initially part of

00:13:21.640 --> 00:13:29.240
[Guest]: the presidencies, you know, we had. So they were in different geographies. And of course,

00:13:29.240 --> 00:13:34.920
[Guest]: the Britishers were very conscious of the fact that the loyalty of the army was absolutely

00:13:34.920 --> 00:13:42.120
[Guest]: vital for retaining power within the country. So then that's how they devised what you described

00:13:42.120 --> 00:13:50.080
[Guest]: as divide and rule. And then it's a very artificial construct called the martial classes. They

00:13:50.080 --> 00:13:56.560
[Guest]: sort of put their faith in these classes and recruited more from there so that there was

00:13:56.560 --> 00:14:01.920
[Guest]: no one particular class which would be strong enough to take over. So they actually put

00:14:01.920 --> 00:14:06.840
[Guest]: the eggs in many baskets. That's what they did. So, you know, they even had the gurkhas

00:14:06.840 --> 00:14:13.480
[Guest]: actually in the Indian army itself. So you could use the gurkhas against somebody else.

00:14:13.480 --> 00:14:19.520
[Guest]: And all this came about from the lesson of 1857 is rooted there. And that's how they

00:14:19.520 --> 00:14:27.400
[Guest]: structured the army itself. So at independence, when we lost whatever had gone to Pakistan,

00:14:27.400 --> 00:14:35.440
[Guest]: the idea of the martial classes and they are being still in the regiments which we were,

00:14:35.440 --> 00:14:40.920
[Guest]: actually that was not the change which was attempted. The change which Jawaharlal Nehru

00:14:40.920 --> 00:14:49.880
[Guest]: was conscious about was of how does he make sure there is sufficient civilian control

00:14:49.880 --> 00:14:57.600
[Guest]: on the military? And that was his focus. Because over a period of time, he saw that the military

00:14:57.600 --> 00:15:03.520
[Guest]: had taken control. So the issue was at the heart of the civil military relationships

00:15:03.520 --> 00:15:12.920
[Guest]: in India, that what sort of control does the civilian exercise on the military? And that's

00:15:12.920 --> 00:15:20.000
[Guest]: where the Ministry of Defense, which was in charge and made some changes. Initially, the

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:26.360
[Guest]: chiefs actually were called the chiefs of staff, and they were also commanders in chief.

00:15:26.360 --> 00:15:32.400
[Guest]: So while they were in Delhi and carrying out their staff activity, when they went to the

00:15:32.400 --> 00:15:41.520
[Guest]: field, then they were commanders in chiefs. And without consultation of the chiefs, the

00:15:41.520 --> 00:15:47.560
[Guest]: commanders in chiefs nomenclature was taken off. There was a big debate about it. The

00:15:47.560 --> 00:15:54.800
[Guest]: chiefs actually protested. But finally, they were overruled and they were told to accept.

00:15:54.800 --> 00:16:00.960
[Guest]: And Nehru made this announcement in Parliament. So Nehru's consciousness or the fact that

00:16:00.960 --> 00:16:09.960
[Guest]: the control need to be exercised has been the main factor initially by which control

00:16:09.960 --> 00:16:16.440
[Guest]: was exercised by the politician. And that control began to be exercised through bureaucratic

00:16:16.440 --> 00:16:23.680
[Guest]: control. And that is where even the idea of attached offices, or that the services were

00:16:23.680 --> 00:16:31.340
[Guest]: attached offices, were all bureaucratic constructions to ensure this control was kept. So as we

00:16:31.340 --> 00:16:40.380
[Guest]: go on, and as we come to the present times, it is this control which has probably kept

00:16:40.380 --> 00:16:46.440
[Guest]: India different from our neighbours and the rest of it. That is one point. And we must

00:16:46.440 --> 00:16:52.400
[Guest]: give credit to the politicians. But I think we should also credit the institutional leadership

00:16:52.400 --> 00:16:59.960
[Guest]: for it. Although I think just the other day, I think somebody has dug up a letter from

00:16:59.960 --> 00:17:06.420
[Guest]: Kariyappa, I think, to the Prime Minister, saying that for some time, the army should

00:17:06.420 --> 00:17:11.260
[Guest]: rule with the help of the President, so that the politics can, you know, there was this,

00:17:11.260 --> 00:17:17.300
[Guest]: I don't know whether it is genuine or not, but I saw, I recently read it. But I think

00:17:17.300 --> 00:17:22.560
[Guest]: it would probably be incorrect because this Kariyappa was supposed to have written much

00:17:22.560 --> 00:17:28.360
[Guest]: after he has left the army, when he's a civilian, it already stood for elections and lost twice

00:17:28.360 --> 00:17:35.060
[Guest]: and so on. So this is not something which he was thinking about when he was in service.

00:17:35.060 --> 00:17:40.100
[Guest]: Whoever was in service and whoever the military chief were very clear, and that's, I think,

00:17:40.100 --> 00:17:45.660
[Guest]: the institutional value, which has been passed down from independence to nowadays, that we

00:17:45.660 --> 00:17:54.180
[Guest]: must remain an apolitical institution. I think this is a value which it is imbibed in the

00:17:54.180 --> 00:17:58.620
[Guest]: military leaders and it is something which is endured. Of course, there will always be

00:17:58.620 --> 00:18:04.300
[Guest]: exceptions to the rule. Somebody might say something at some point in time, but I don't

00:18:04.300 --> 00:18:10.820
[Guest]: think you would find anybody who is wearing the uniform saying something contradictory

00:18:10.820 --> 00:18:14.900
[Guest]: to this, it would be very difficult. It would have been said by somebody who was already

00:18:14.900 --> 00:18:20.540
[Guest]: out of uniform. So I think there are two things here. One is the consciousness of the political

00:18:20.540 --> 00:18:27.580
[Guest]: leaders which made sure that the control is exercised. And the other one was of the military

00:18:27.580 --> 00:18:35.020
[Guest]: as an institution itself, which sort of embedded in itself the value of being apolitical. So

00:18:35.020 --> 00:18:38.660
[Guest]: I think that's why both these things in combination has kept it the way it is.

00:18:38.660 --> 00:18:42.180
[Amit Varma]: In fact, it's interesting that, you know, when he took over, General Kariyappa famously

00:18:42.180 --> 00:18:47.180
[Amit Varma]: sent out a circular to the officers he commanded saying that we must stay away from politics.

00:18:47.180 --> 00:18:51.740
[Amit Varma]: But after he retired in 1953, and again quoting from Wilkinson's book, he argued on several

00:18:51.740 --> 00:18:56.180
[Amit Varma]: occasions for court, a suspension of civil liberties, the imposition of emergency precedence

00:18:56.180 --> 00:19:01.540
[Amit Varma]: rule on the states, the disbanding of political parties, suspension of parliament until law

00:19:01.540 --> 00:19:05.620
[Amit Varma]: and order had been restored, and the replacement of universal suffrage with a franchise that

00:19:05.620 --> 00:19:11.580
[Amit Varma]: was restricted to literates. But this is all, like you said, after retirement and no serving

00:19:11.580 --> 00:19:17.580
[Amit Varma]: officer has ever kind of said things of this sort. What was sort of really interesting

00:19:17.580 --> 00:19:22.460
[Amit Varma]: like along with what you pointed out that a lot of the control was, you know, the Defense

00:19:22.460 --> 00:19:27.480
[Amit Varma]: Ministry was on the ascendant and a lot of that control was taken away from the army.

00:19:27.480 --> 00:19:34.260
[Amit Varma]: But another sort of direction that Nehru tried to move in was to change the martial composition

00:19:34.260 --> 00:19:39.940
[Amit Varma]: of the army itself. And it's interesting that in 1949, the Indian government basically announced

00:19:39.940 --> 00:19:45.140
[Amit Varma]: that we shall now be open to all able-bodied men from all across the country. But there

00:19:45.140 --> 00:19:50.180
[Amit Varma]: was a caveat here, which did sort of affect the way things worked out in practice. Again,

00:19:50.180 --> 00:19:55.040
[Amit Varma]: I'll quote Wilkinson, quote, the specific wording of the army promises and orders given

00:19:55.040 --> 00:20:00.100
[Amit Varma]: in 1949, which stated that new infantry and artillery regiments would be open to members

00:20:00.100 --> 00:20:04.100
[Amit Varma]: of all provinces, and that all other branches of the army would be open to members of all

00:20:04.100 --> 00:20:08.920
[Amit Varma]: provinces had much less effect in broadening out the army than most politicians thought

00:20:08.920 --> 00:20:14.380
[Amit Varma]: it would. This was because, as the generals knew, the infantry and armored corps had expanded

00:20:14.380 --> 00:20:19.420
[Amit Varma]: in World War II by adding new battalions to existing class regiments, rather than through

00:20:19.420 --> 00:20:24.780
[Amit Varma]: the logistically much more complex and uncertain step of adding whole new regiments, training

00:20:24.780 --> 00:20:28.980
[Amit Varma]: centers, recruitment areas, and fighting traditions. Since independence, for instance, the Punjab

00:20:28.980 --> 00:20:33.980
[Amit Varma]: regiment, which recruits mainly Sikhs and Dogras, has increased from 5 to 29 battalions,

00:20:33.980 --> 00:20:39.820
[Amit Varma]: where the Rajputana rifles has increased from 6 to 21 battalions, because expansion has

00:20:39.820 --> 00:20:46.800
[Amit Varma]: largely happened through the existing regiments. So now, while there is this tendency from

00:20:46.800 --> 00:20:54.300
[Amit Varma]: within the army of sort of finding a Jugaaru way around actually changing the ethnic composition,

00:20:54.300 --> 00:20:59.340
[Amit Varma]: you do find that, for example, one of the ways in which Nehru sort of controlled that

00:20:59.340 --> 00:21:05.040
[Amit Varma]: was through making sure that the chief of army staff reflected far more diversity. So

00:21:05.040 --> 00:21:10.440
[Amit Varma]: in fact, in between 49 and 79, if I remember correctly, there was only one chief of army

00:21:10.440 --> 00:21:15.940
[Amit Varma]: staff from the so-called martial races, which is the Punjabis, which was General Thapar

00:21:15.940 --> 00:21:19.880
[Amit Varma]: after we came to Krishnamandir and appointed him. But the rest were from sort of all over

00:21:19.880 --> 00:21:24.920
[Amit Varma]: the place. Despite the fact that at the time of independence, the army, you know, 50% of

00:21:24.920 --> 00:21:31.360
[Amit Varma]: the officers were Punjabis and 26% Sikhs. So it's kind of interesting that the political

00:21:31.360 --> 00:21:38.200
[Amit Varma]: class is trying to weave the army in a particular direction. And the army itself is sort of

00:21:38.200 --> 00:21:39.760
[Guest]: how do you view it?

00:21:39.760 --> 00:21:46.600
[Guest]: Yeah, firstly, especially about the fact that the chiefs were chosen because of their, from

00:21:46.600 --> 00:21:52.580
[Guest]: their regional roots. I don't think that was ever the case. And I don't think that was

00:21:52.580 --> 00:21:59.680
[Guest]: a point of consideration. Chiefs were purely chosen, depending upon their seniority and

00:21:59.680 --> 00:22:05.960
[Guest]: their merit and the combination of both. I don't think this issue really is true. But

00:22:05.960 --> 00:22:06.960
[Amit Varma]: I think...

00:22:06.960 --> 00:22:08.960
[Guest]: I mean, this is what Wilkinson says.

00:22:08.960 --> 00:22:14.360
[Guest]: I agree. I just sort of disagree with Wilkinson on this point. But I think the other point

00:22:14.360 --> 00:22:20.960
[Guest]: which he makes, which was about the composition of the fighting arms, which was the infantry

00:22:20.960 --> 00:22:27.720
[Guest]: and the armoured corps. In fact, I belong to a regiment, which was the first regiment

00:22:27.720 --> 00:22:35.800
[Guest]: raised by that time General Kariyappa, which was an all India class composition. That means

00:22:35.800 --> 00:22:43.160
[Guest]: we could recruit anybody from any part and that we remain, therefore, the only regiment,

00:22:43.160 --> 00:22:49.880
[Guest]: which is the fighting among these old regiments, which is all India class. The rest have continued

00:22:49.880 --> 00:22:56.880
[Guest]: to be what they were, which means the Rajputana rifles, primarily from Rajasthan, UP, Punjabis,

00:22:56.880 --> 00:23:04.400
[Guest]: Sikh, Sikhalai, Bihar, Madras, and so on. This is the regimental system which has refused

00:23:04.400 --> 00:23:10.880
[Guest]: to change. And the only attempt to make this change, which is serious, was after Blue Star

00:23:10.880 --> 00:23:17.120
[Guest]: when the Sikh regiments, some of them had mutinied. And actually, there was this study

00:23:17.120 --> 00:23:25.520
[Guest]: which was ordered and there was major resistance from the infantry regiments themselves, because

00:23:25.520 --> 00:23:32.160
[Guest]: the infantry leadership felt that the fact that you could have groups of men from a particular

00:23:32.160 --> 00:23:39.880
[Guest]: geography always had strengths as far as fighting is concerned, food habits and so on. Although

00:23:39.880 --> 00:23:45.360
[Guest]: all these beliefs have been demolished by the regiment I come from, that we get people

00:23:45.360 --> 00:23:53.160
[Guest]: and we still have, we got enough laurels of this idea, but it has endured. It has not

00:23:53.160 --> 00:23:59.240
[Guest]: been possible to actually have an army with the fighting arm. All the rest have changed.

00:23:59.240 --> 00:24:03.960
[Guest]: The artillery has changed. The engineers have changed. Everybody else has nearly changed,

00:24:03.960 --> 00:24:10.400
[Guest]: not fully, nearly changed. The infant, the fighting arms have only the new raisings,

00:24:10.400 --> 00:24:18.280
[Guest]: whatever was used, the new battalions, they have mostly, especially outside the fighting

00:24:18.280 --> 00:24:23.400
[Guest]: arms, mostly been based on all India class composition. So we have this anomaly. And

00:24:23.400 --> 00:24:31.440
[Guest]: in my personal view, we should at some point in time migrate into an all India class composition.

00:24:31.440 --> 00:24:36.920
[Guest]: And I'll tell you why I'm saying this, because I come from an all India class regiment. You

00:24:36.920 --> 00:24:45.080
[Guest]: see, if you were in a Gurkha battalion, the Gurkha battalion will have strengths, which

00:24:45.080 --> 00:24:50.840
[Guest]: are confined to the strength of the Gurkhas, which means they'll be good at boxing, good

00:24:50.840 --> 00:24:56.280
[Guest]: at boxing, but they won't be good swimmers. They won't be good basketballers. Whereas

00:24:56.280 --> 00:25:01.360
[Guest]: if you come to my regiment and my unit, you'll find that because of the all India class,

00:25:01.360 --> 00:25:09.600
[Guest]: we have strength from across the spectrum. So the strength will always be better if you

00:25:09.600 --> 00:25:16.160
[Guest]: have an all India class. And therefore, this idea, but you know, the orthodox infantry

00:25:16.160 --> 00:25:21.760
[Guest]: leaders would disagree with me because they belong to that school of thought where they

00:25:21.760 --> 00:25:26.840
[Guest]: have been brought up from a Madras regiment. The idea that a Madras regiment can actually

00:25:26.840 --> 00:25:32.000
[Guest]: have an all India class will be anathema to the very system by which they have been grown

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:37.960
[Guest]: up. And not that those battalions are as good or as bad as mine, but I would think from

00:25:37.960 --> 00:25:45.080
[Guest]: a much larger perspective, the Indian armed forces must finally all be all India class.

00:25:45.080 --> 00:25:51.560
[Guest]: If we have to migrate, in fact, the study which I'm talking about, which was done actually

00:25:51.560 --> 00:25:57.400
[Guest]: suggested to do that, we should do this in 30 years time. Of course, in India, if somebody

00:25:57.400 --> 00:26:01.440
[Guest]: is suggesting to do anything in 30 years time, that means they know that it's not going to

00:26:01.440 --> 00:26:08.520
[Guest]: be done. It was never done. So we had some experimentation and finally it was put to

00:26:08.520 --> 00:26:12.880
[Guest]: sleep. So we have not made that change, but we should, in my point.

00:26:12.880 --> 00:26:16.760
[Amit Varma]: No, in fact, just thinking aloud, I mean, the whole thinking about the martial classes

00:26:16.760 --> 00:26:21.880
[Amit Varma]: was of course based on the very simplistic way in which the British tried to make sense

00:26:21.880 --> 00:26:25.640
[Amit Varma]: of India when they first came. I mean, I had an episode with Manu Pillay a while back where

00:26:25.640 --> 00:26:29.780
[Amit Varma]: we spoke about caste and, you know, Manu made the point that it's the British who made it

00:26:29.780 --> 00:26:33.480
[Amit Varma]: fashionable to look at the entire country through the lens of the Varna system, but

00:26:33.480 --> 00:26:38.120
[Amit Varma]: caste actually was far more complicated than that. And this whole theory of the martial

00:26:38.120 --> 00:26:42.720
[Amit Varma]: races also seems to me a way of the British just trying to quickly categorize everything

00:26:42.720 --> 00:26:48.120
[Amit Varma]: for the purpose of making sense of it. But it's all nonsense. But nevertheless, the fact

00:26:48.120 --> 00:26:52.760
[Amit Varma]: is that a lot of the thinking percolates through and which leads to this sort of very amusing

00:26:52.760 --> 00:26:58.600
[Amit Varma]: construction where there is a certain set of conventional thinkers who say that, no,

00:26:58.600 --> 00:27:02.000
[Amit Varma]: within a battalion, you must have like the Punjabis together and the Gorkhas together

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:05.960
[Amit Varma]: because there'll be better integration and there'll be better fighting units because

00:27:05.960 --> 00:27:10.040
[Amit Varma]: they'll fight better together, which as you point out is not true, but that belief nevertheless

00:27:10.040 --> 00:27:14.920
[Amit Varma]: persists. And at the same time, there was this determination within the political classes

00:27:14.920 --> 00:27:20.240
[Amit Varma]: that we must have an all India composition because that reduces the chances of the army

00:27:20.240 --> 00:27:24.720
[Amit Varma]: coming together against us because you have less chance of that kind of consensus forming

00:27:24.720 --> 00:27:30.160
[Amit Varma]: if you have diversity. And one of the compromises was that the army's infantry battalions, for

00:27:30.160 --> 00:27:35.080
[Amit Varma]: example, were structured in these fixed class units, where, for example, you'll have the

00:27:35.080 --> 00:27:40.240
[Amit Varma]: Punjab Regiment Battalion have two companies of Sikhs and two of Dogras and a typical JNK

00:27:40.240 --> 00:27:44.480
[Amit Varma]: Rifles Battalion will have four different groups, Dogras, Gorkhas, Sikhs and Muslims,

00:27:44.480 --> 00:27:48.960
[Amit Varma]: thereby also satisfying those who say that, no, you need to keep the Sikhs together and

00:27:48.960 --> 00:27:53.680
[Amit Varma]: also ensuring some kind of diversity within the regiment. So they're not actually going

00:27:53.680 --> 00:27:56.360
[Amit Varma]: to stand up and plot against the government, as it were.

00:27:56.360 --> 00:28:04.480
[Guest]: You know, India is strong when we are mixed up. The more identities that we have is where

00:28:04.480 --> 00:28:09.000
[Guest]: the problem actually is. It's not by demolishing these identities. I'm not talking about that.

00:28:09.000 --> 00:28:14.880
[Guest]: I'm not talking about that at all. But the fact is, when we are together, then we bring

00:28:14.880 --> 00:28:19.640
[Guest]: our individual strengths because the strength comes from the diversity, that you can have

00:28:19.640 --> 00:28:24.600
[Guest]: different strengths in the same place because they are mixed. The example I gave you of

00:28:24.600 --> 00:28:32.240
[Guest]: a Gorkha Battalion, or let's say you have people from Bihar and you have Adivasis there,

00:28:32.240 --> 00:28:37.760
[Guest]: they'll be very good at hockey, but they may not be good at something else. So if you have

00:28:37.760 --> 00:28:43.800
[Guest]: everybody mixed, you'll be strong in everybody. So the idea that we should have all India

00:28:43.800 --> 00:28:51.840
[Guest]: class is something which has been accepted officially, but we are not able to do it because

00:28:51.840 --> 00:28:56.800
[Guest]: entrenched beliefs and interests keep that from happening.

00:28:56.800 --> 00:29:04.120
[Guest]: Although, let me tell you, it is now only confined to the, which is a large part, which

00:29:04.120 --> 00:29:09.400
[Guest]: is the fighting arm with the infantry regiments. And I think some armoured corps regiments,

00:29:09.400 --> 00:29:15.400
[Guest]: I think armoured corps also has shifted. So it still remains an infantry sort of fortress.

00:29:15.400 --> 00:29:19.480
[Amit Varma]: But you are, of course, in an all India class, so it doesn't apply to you. But within the

00:29:19.480 --> 00:29:25.480
[Amit Varma]: army, are there then these entrenched in-group, out-group stereotypes, like within a Sikh

00:29:25.480 --> 00:29:29.280
[Amit Varma]: regiment, would you have an internal sense that, oh, we are better than those guys, and

00:29:29.280 --> 00:29:30.280
[Guest]: so on?

00:29:30.280 --> 00:29:34.520
[Guest]: So that's the point that they believe, and then this is the school of thought, that when

00:29:34.520 --> 00:29:41.680
[Guest]: you are part of a fighting arm, you're fighting spirit, and your camaraderie comes, is more

00:29:41.680 --> 00:29:47.840
[Guest]: stronger when you're with your own people. That's what the belief is. I'm saying that

00:29:47.840 --> 00:29:52.360
[Guest]: I've come from an all India class regiment, and we have demolished that belief because

00:29:52.360 --> 00:29:57.280
[Guest]: we have actually been in combat, our units have been in combat, and they have performed

00:29:57.280 --> 00:30:04.120
[Guest]: as well as any other. So this belief itself has been disproved, but yet it endures because

00:30:04.120 --> 00:30:05.640
[Amit Varma]: people still have that belief.

00:30:05.640 --> 00:30:11.240
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, before we move on, I'll quickly sum up, you know, three of the possible reasons

00:30:11.240 --> 00:30:15.600
[Amit Varma]: that have been cited by Wilkinson for why our civil-military relations did not go the

00:30:15.600 --> 00:30:20.640
[Amit Varma]: same way as Pakistan did. And tell me if you have something to add or elaborate upon these,

00:30:20.640 --> 00:30:27.480
[Amit Varma]: where point one he makes is that the socio-economic strategic inheritance of Pakistan was far

00:30:27.480 --> 00:30:31.680
[Amit Varma]: worse in 1947 compared to India, because they not only had to look after their border with

00:30:31.680 --> 00:30:35.520
[Amit Varma]: us, they had to look after their border with Afghanistan, and they were separated from

00:30:35.520 --> 00:30:39.880
[Amit Varma]: East Pakistan for so long. And because of this, they needed to sort of strengthen the

00:30:39.880 --> 00:30:45.760
[Amit Varma]: army and also the ethnic makeup, the ethnic imbalance in their army was worsened. Ours

00:30:45.760 --> 00:30:50.680
[Amit Varma]: was slightly better, but because of the flows of partition, theirs remained very Punjab

00:30:50.680 --> 00:30:55.320
[Amit Varma]: and Pashtun dominated with practically no Bengali influence at all, which, you know,

00:30:55.320 --> 00:30:59.480
[Amit Varma]: had a huge role to play given that the majority of the population was actually in what was

00:30:59.480 --> 00:31:00.680
[Amit Varma]: then East Pakistan.

00:31:00.680 --> 00:31:06.040
[Amit Varma]: The second factor, according to Wilkinson, is that the political institutionalization

00:31:06.040 --> 00:31:11.800
[Amit Varma]: of the Congress party compared to the Muslim League, that it had far deeper roots, far

00:31:11.800 --> 00:31:16.000
[Amit Varma]: greater support. So, therefore, when they set out to reform the army, you knew that

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:20.840
[Amit Varma]: they have the popular support and you can't sort of mess with these guys. And plus they

00:31:20.840 --> 00:31:26.080
[Amit Varma]: were representative in terms of the ethnic and religious distribution within the Congress,

00:31:26.080 --> 00:31:31.000
[Amit Varma]: which of course was not the case with the Muslim League in Pakistan. And third, what

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:34.560
[Amit Varma]: you've referred to the specific coup proofing and the balancing measures that the new Indian

00:31:34.560 --> 00:31:39.360
[Amit Varma]: state undertook, partly because you had these decades of thinking which had gone on on how

00:31:39.360 --> 00:31:44.520
[Amit Varma]: to control the military when we get independent, because this was something that they were

00:31:44.520 --> 00:31:50.240
[Amit Varma]: sort of worried about. Did the China war change how people thought about the Indian military

00:31:50.240 --> 00:31:54.440
[Amit Varma]: and how the military looked at itself? Because, you know, after the loss to China, there would

00:31:54.440 --> 00:31:57.680
[Amit Varma]: have been the imperative to just grow the army as fast as possible.

00:31:57.680 --> 00:32:05.720
[Guest]: China war actually was, of course, the defense minister had to resign. And it also cast a

00:32:05.720 --> 00:32:15.360
[Guest]: shadow on the civil military relationship in terms of whether how much of interference

00:32:15.360 --> 00:32:22.120
[Guest]: should they be by the politicians in the military affairs, especially its leadership and even

00:32:22.120 --> 00:32:27.720
[Guest]: actually deciding them. There was no dialogue. They were told to do things which they were

00:32:27.720 --> 00:32:32.480
[Guest]: not capable of doing because they didn't have the equipment and so on. So the main thing

00:32:32.480 --> 00:32:39.920
[Guest]: which came out of 1962 was that there was an insufficient dialogue to actually be able

00:32:39.920 --> 00:32:45.400
[Guest]: to, the army had to be told what to be prepared for. If he's not given the way with all to

00:32:45.400 --> 00:32:52.000
[Guest]: flick. So it worked both ways. So the army had its own pathologies which afflicted it

00:32:52.000 --> 00:32:56.480
[Guest]: and the politician had it. It came together in 1962. But that's probably the lowest point

00:32:56.480 --> 00:33:02.520
[Guest]: at which we, from where we must think that we have only improved from there on. Because

00:33:02.520 --> 00:33:08.040
[Guest]: 1962, certainly on both sides of the civil military divide, the military also was not

00:33:08.040 --> 00:33:14.200
[Guest]: seen in a good light. And so did the politicians. So one can blame the other, but we must admit

00:33:14.200 --> 00:33:19.360
[Guest]: that everybody was to blame because it can't be just one side that you blame and the other

00:33:19.360 --> 00:33:26.000
[Guest]: doesn't take it. So it has to be a joint affair. So from that low point, I think, is a realization

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:31.760
[Guest]: that things need to change, whether it just changed fast enough or sufficiently is a matter

00:33:31.760 --> 00:33:34.760
[Guest]: of debate. But that's the lowest point.

00:33:34.760 --> 00:33:39.040
[Amit Varma]: And I guess at this point, you know, there are these dual imperatives. One is the imperative

00:33:39.040 --> 00:33:43.640
[Amit Varma]: that the army has to expand massively. But the other is the political imperative, which

00:33:43.640 --> 00:33:48.240
[Amit Varma]: is still there, which Nehru articulated that we don't want the army to get too powerful

00:33:48.240 --> 00:33:51.840
[Amit Varma]: because we don't want a situation like in Pakistan, because these are still the young

00:33:51.840 --> 00:33:57.280
[Amit Varma]: years of the Indian Union has been like 15 years since independence and so on. And one

00:33:57.280 --> 00:34:02.920
[Amit Varma]: of the ways in which they kind of did this was by far more surveillance of top generals,

00:34:02.920 --> 00:34:09.040
[Amit Varma]: like Lieutenant General S.D. Verma wrote a book in 1988, where he kind of, the book is

00:34:09.040 --> 00:34:14.280
[Amit Varma]: called to serve with honors, where he kind of described how his telephone used to be

00:34:14.280 --> 00:34:20.960
[Amit Varma]: tapped. And when he once went, he wanted to talk to the commanding officer, General Timaya,

00:34:20.960 --> 00:34:25.160
[Amit Varma]: they actually, and this was in Kashmir, the two of them took a boat out in the middle

00:34:25.160 --> 00:34:29.920
[Amit Varma]: of the Nagin Lake as it then was to make sure that they're not being overheard. And typically

00:34:29.920 --> 00:34:34.400
[Amit Varma]: you take such precautions when you're worried about being overheard by a foreign country.

00:34:34.400 --> 00:34:41.280
[Amit Varma]: And in this case, it was sort of, you know, your political partners, so to say. So was

00:34:41.280 --> 00:34:45.800
[Amit Varma]: this sort of an early distrust between the army and the politicians which gradually settled

00:34:45.800 --> 00:34:48.880
[Amit Varma]: down to some kind of equilibrium?

00:34:48.880 --> 00:34:53.680
[Guest]: I think the distrust would be a natural thing to happen because just look at the political

00:34:53.680 --> 00:34:58.440
[Guest]: leaders at that point in time, not only in our neighborhood and even in the rest, especially

00:34:58.440 --> 00:35:03.960
[Guest]: in Africa and so on, there were militaries which were actually taking over government.

00:35:03.960 --> 00:35:10.600
[Guest]: So it was more the norm than anything else. So why wouldn't it have sensitized our political

00:35:10.600 --> 00:35:17.840
[Guest]: leadership to be cautious about our own? Whether they tapped their phones, how they have kept

00:35:17.840 --> 00:35:23.480
[Guest]: vigilance on them, I'm not aware of. But if they did, we must know that they would have

00:35:23.480 --> 00:35:31.200
[Guest]: done it for good reason, not because they wanted to hear what the conversation was,

00:35:31.200 --> 00:35:38.120
[Guest]: because what was at the back of their minds was the fact that this possibility existed

00:35:38.120 --> 00:35:46.380
[Guest]: if this happened. And I think no political leadership ever should ever be complacent

00:35:46.380 --> 00:35:54.720
[Guest]: about this, because that I think is the duty of the civilian, because the military has

00:35:54.720 --> 00:36:05.560
[Guest]: its own way of gathering a particular type of momentum, which must be kept under control.

00:36:05.560 --> 00:36:11.960
[Guest]: To say that the military can be autonomously do its job, and that is why this whole theory

00:36:11.960 --> 00:36:18.840
[Guest]: of civil-military relationship is about the fact that one needs to understand the other.

00:36:18.840 --> 00:36:25.320
[Guest]: And as far as the civilian is concerned, there must be civilian control. The complaint in

00:36:25.320 --> 00:36:29.960
[Guest]: our case has always been that it's not civilian control, it's bureaucratic control. And that's

00:36:29.960 --> 00:36:34.800
[Guest]: where the military has always been complaining about. But that bureaucratic control, probably

00:36:34.800 --> 00:36:39.680
[Guest]: the bureaucracy will say was being exercised on behalf of the politicians, and the politicians

00:36:39.680 --> 00:36:48.480
[Guest]: are actually given that. So the point at issue is, I don't think at any time, in a democracy,

00:36:48.480 --> 00:36:55.920
[Guest]: should the civilians be complacent about, let the military have an autonomous existence,

00:36:55.920 --> 00:37:02.120
[Guest]: and they can do what they want. I think they must always be watchful, because it is the

00:37:02.120 --> 00:37:09.840
[Guest]: natural proclivity of the military to claim that autonomy, because they think that the

00:37:09.840 --> 00:37:19.840
[Guest]: sphere in which they are actually is so specialized that nobody should interfere in it. Which

00:37:19.840 --> 00:37:28.800
[Guest]: is where the contradiction is that today, we're a nuclear power. Certainly the military

00:37:28.800 --> 00:37:35.240
[Guest]: cannot be, as one model suggests, that military will be told what to do by the politicians,

00:37:35.240 --> 00:37:40.280
[Guest]: and the military will be given full freedom to do the way they want to. I'm afraid I don't

00:37:40.280 --> 00:37:45.920
[Guest]: agree with that model, because everything that you do, and the type of wars that you

00:37:45.920 --> 00:37:53.480
[Guest]: fight today, especially under a nuclear arm, has to have civilian control over it. And

00:37:53.480 --> 00:38:02.920
[Guest]: I think the person who describes this best is Clausewitz, where he says that the rational

00:38:02.920 --> 00:38:10.480
[Guest]: part of military affairs, once military is in action, can only be controlled by the politicians,

00:38:10.480 --> 00:38:16.880
[Guest]: because he represents the rationality. Otherwise, military acquires a momentum of its own, which

00:38:16.880 --> 00:38:23.720
[Guest]: is unstoppable. So the very idea that there should not be civilian control and military

00:38:23.720 --> 00:38:28.680
[Guest]: can be autonomous, when given the job, I do not agree with that. The model which we probably

00:38:28.680 --> 00:38:35.240
[Guest]: have, and I think Kargil is a good example of how, despite the objections of the military,

00:38:35.240 --> 00:38:41.880
[Guest]: or not even consulting them, clearly it was laid down that you will not cross the line

00:38:41.880 --> 00:38:49.560
[Guest]: of control. To a soldier, and purely in operational terms, it doesn't make any sense.

00:38:49.560 --> 00:38:53.640
[Amit Varma]: And what you're saying is that those geopolitical reasons must always take precedence over military

00:38:53.640 --> 00:38:54.640
[Guest]: reasons.

00:38:54.640 --> 00:38:58.560
[Guest]: Of course. And the Indian politicians at that time just laid it out. I mean, they refused

00:38:58.560 --> 00:39:03.760
[Guest]: to budge from it. So they did not even consult the military about the decision. They just

00:39:03.760 --> 00:39:09.520
[Guest]: told them that this is our decision. And that I think is the right thing to do. Because

00:39:09.520 --> 00:39:15.080
[Guest]: if, and especially where nuclear power today, it becomes more so, because you can't allow

00:39:15.080 --> 00:39:20.240
[Guest]: the military to do what they want when there are nuclear weapons which can come into play.

00:39:20.240 --> 00:39:26.760
[Guest]: So I think this idea, the main complaint has always been from the armed forces that this

00:39:26.760 --> 00:39:35.080
[Guest]: control the armed forces accept is required, but it cannot be exercised purely in terms

00:39:35.080 --> 00:39:43.480
[Guest]: of procedures and bureaucratic control, especially as far as defense planning is concerned. While

00:39:43.480 --> 00:39:48.920
[Guest]: nobody intervenes in operational terms, once you're given your constraints that you can't

00:39:48.920 --> 00:39:54.920
[Guest]: do this, but where the complaint has been mostly is that you're not sufficiently in

00:39:54.920 --> 00:40:00.240
[Guest]: the decision making when you have to acquire, when you're to modernize, you need the type

00:40:00.240 --> 00:40:05.480
[Guest]: of equipment for the type of threats. That's been the main complaint. It's not about how

00:40:05.480 --> 00:40:11.320
[Guest]: wars are to be fought and so on. That is not the thing. It's about preparing for the war

00:40:11.320 --> 00:40:17.920
[Guest]: and the wherewithal which has to be made available to it, which means these are political decisions.

00:40:17.920 --> 00:40:23.800
[Guest]: What is the budget going to be? Where can you buy it from? All these decisions, some

00:40:23.800 --> 00:40:29.700
[Guest]: of it, and the large, this thing has always been that instead of political control, bureaucratic

00:40:29.700 --> 00:40:32.320
[Guest]: control has been exercised. That's been the complaint.

00:40:32.320 --> 00:40:36.240
[Amit Varma]: So I have three sort of follow up thoughts on this. One, of course, is, I mean, it's

00:40:36.240 --> 00:40:40.000
[Amit Varma]: very interesting to me that you should say that I obviously agree with you that you should

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:45.760
[Amit Varma]: say that civilian control over military is paramount. But it seems to me that, you know,

00:40:45.760 --> 00:40:51.160
[Amit Varma]: tapping of phones was kind of a crude way of doing that. Like, you know, what SD Varma

00:40:51.160 --> 00:40:55.040
[Amit Varma]: describes in his autobiography is that after General Timaya, who was the chief of armed

00:40:55.040 --> 00:40:59.800
[Amit Varma]: staff, he had a fight with VK Krishnamurthy and he left. And then SD Varma called him

00:40:59.800 --> 00:41:03.240
[Amit Varma]: to commiserate. And he realized that after he had called him to commiserate, he was cut

00:41:03.240 --> 00:41:07.120
[Amit Varma]: off by the powers that be, which basically means that they had listened to his telephone

00:41:07.120 --> 00:41:11.520
[Amit Varma]: call, which is how he first found out about the tapping, which he later confirmed.

00:41:11.520 --> 00:41:16.360
[Amit Varma]: And it strikes me that it's rather than resort to crude measures, like actually surveilling

00:41:16.360 --> 00:41:21.200
[Amit Varma]: your top army officers, it's actually far better to have rules of the game in place,

00:41:21.200 --> 00:41:25.120
[Amit Varma]: which introduce their own safeguards, which brings me to the next question where I'd like

00:41:25.120 --> 00:41:30.840
[Amit Varma]: you to elaborate upon what you mean by the distinction between civil control and bureaucratic

00:41:30.840 --> 00:41:35.560
[Amit Varma]: control. That if one accepts the principle that the civilian administration should have

00:41:35.560 --> 00:41:39.920
[Amit Varma]: control over the army, over the armed forces, then what is this distinction? I mean, they'll

00:41:39.920 --> 00:41:45.720
[Amit Varma]: do it through bureaucrats, obviously. So what is this distinction and where is it a problem?

00:41:45.720 --> 00:41:51.200
[Guest]: Actually, this goes to the heart of the civil military issue, that the military instrument

00:41:51.200 --> 00:41:59.160
[Guest]: has got its peculiarities, which the military probably knows best about the instrument.

00:41:59.160 --> 00:42:06.320
[Guest]: The civilian and the civil political leadership are actually not conversant with this instrument.

00:42:06.320 --> 00:42:12.400
[Guest]: And that is why this instrument firstly has to be shaped to meet the needs of what the

00:42:12.400 --> 00:42:20.240
[Guest]: politicians want, which means the politicians have to first tell the military, give the

00:42:20.240 --> 00:42:26.080
[Guest]: political guidance to the military, that this is what we would want you to do if you have

00:42:26.080 --> 00:42:33.240
[Guest]: to do anything, which is the political guidance which is given. The military has to translate

00:42:33.240 --> 00:42:41.640
[Guest]: that political guidance into military terms and shape the instrument that it wants. When

00:42:41.640 --> 00:42:49.200
[Guest]: it does that, and the military is the best thing for this translation. But firstly, therefore,

00:42:49.200 --> 00:42:55.560
[Guest]: the military has to understand what this political guidance is. The politician has to understand

00:42:55.560 --> 00:42:59.480
[Guest]: what sort of political guidance should be given to the military. So there has to be

00:42:59.480 --> 00:43:05.160
[Guest]: this understanding between the two because they belong to two different worlds. The political

00:43:05.160 --> 00:43:13.400
[Guest]: leadership is normally, unlike the military, they are short term in their outlook. And

00:43:13.400 --> 00:43:18.880
[Guest]: also they are a contingent. They work for in terms of what is the contingencies. Whereas

00:43:18.880 --> 00:43:23.320
[Guest]: this instrument cannot be dealt with like that. This instrument has to be dealt with

00:43:23.320 --> 00:43:24.520
[Guest]: as a long term instrument.

00:43:24.520 --> 00:43:29.400
[Amit Varma]: Can you give me a concrete illustration of that for a layperson like me so I can understand

00:43:29.400 --> 00:43:36.600
[Amit Varma]: it better of a, what is the political purpose, which results in a particular military instrument,

00:43:36.600 --> 00:43:41.240
[Amit Varma]: which then can be screwed up by the short termism of the political class?

00:43:41.240 --> 00:43:48.400
[Guest]: So suppose we have, let's say, two adversaries, one is north and one is to the west. Now it

00:43:48.400 --> 00:43:57.480
[Guest]: is for the political leaders to tell you what sort of political objectives, if there is

00:43:57.480 --> 00:44:04.600
[Guest]: a war, that you need to achieve as far as Pakistan is concerned. This is what you should

00:44:04.600 --> 00:44:12.040
[Guest]: be able to achieve, or if there is a war here. Now this political objectives cannot be crystallized

00:44:12.040 --> 00:44:18.640
[Guest]: unless there is a dialogue between the civil leadership and the military. It cannot be

00:44:18.640 --> 00:44:26.560
[Guest]: done independently of the military itself because it requires an understanding of the

00:44:26.560 --> 00:44:31.840
[Guest]: military instrument and the military instrument has to understand what these guys have won.

00:44:31.840 --> 00:44:38.600
[Guest]: And this is the dialogue which will only make it possible. So then you need to have mechanisms

00:44:38.600 --> 00:44:41.120
[Guest]: by which this dialogue is taking place.

00:44:41.120 --> 00:44:46.960
[Guest]: One of our greatest deficiencies has been this, that there has been lack of political

00:44:46.960 --> 00:44:55.000
[Guest]: guidance to the military itself. So in the lack of guidance, the military assumes certain

00:44:55.000 --> 00:44:59.400
[Guest]: things and decides that we won't. Now in the military also, there are three different services.

00:44:59.400 --> 00:45:04.480
[Guest]: So it's well possible that all the three services will think in three different ways. The Navy

00:45:04.480 --> 00:45:10.400
[Guest]: will think about what is in the maritime arena. The Air Force will think about air power and

00:45:10.400 --> 00:45:15.520
[Guest]: this is about land power. There's nobody who's going to put it together and that's why you

00:45:15.520 --> 00:45:23.600
[Guest]: need structural mechanisms for this to take place. And all this came to be and realized

00:45:23.600 --> 00:45:32.240
[Guest]: only after the Kargil war, that we need firstly political guidance. And that is why we had

00:45:32.240 --> 00:45:37.880
[Guest]: these new institutions like the National Security Council Secretariat, where I have served.

00:45:37.880 --> 00:45:45.280
[Guest]: But yet India still doesn't have a national security doctrine or a strategy, which is

00:45:45.280 --> 00:45:50.920
[Guest]: the mother document from which the rest has to flow. So in the absence of that mother

00:45:50.920 --> 00:45:56.920
[Guest]: document, there are certain assumptions, which the defense ministry itself is making, probably

00:45:56.920 --> 00:46:02.640
[Guest]: with some guidance. And that is why they have, we have now, they have made a defense planning

00:46:02.640 --> 00:46:10.200
[Guest]: committee with the NSA as its head, and it's actually located within the Ministry of Defense.

00:46:10.200 --> 00:46:15.080
[Guest]: But these are all ad hoc mechanisms. They're not structures, which will probably endure

00:46:15.080 --> 00:46:21.840
[Guest]: for long. So one of the problem has been, there is less understanding of the politicians

00:46:21.840 --> 00:46:29.880
[Guest]: of what this military is capable and not capable of. And 1962 is a good example of when Nehru

00:46:29.880 --> 00:46:35.240
[Guest]: said, you know, you throw them out. I mean, he gave me the same statement, throw the Chinese

00:46:35.240 --> 00:46:40.880
[Guest]: out. He had no idea what the capability then of the armed forces were, because, you know,

00:46:40.880 --> 00:46:45.760
[Guest]: by which time they were under recoup, they did not have the road infrastructure, although

00:46:45.760 --> 00:46:50.880
[Guest]: enough studies were done before the 1950s, which said that we must develop this infrastructure

00:46:50.880 --> 00:46:57.320
[Guest]: against China, but it was not done. So this, this lack of understanding of each other is

00:46:57.320 --> 00:47:03.360
[Guest]: what is at the heart of a civil military problems. And therefore, you need a constant dialogue

00:47:03.360 --> 00:47:04.760
[Amit Varma]: between the two.

00:47:04.760 --> 00:47:09.080
[Amit Varma]: So the illustration that comes to mind and tell me if it works as an illustration of

00:47:09.080 --> 00:47:14.920
[Amit Varma]: what you're describing, is in fact, the Bangladesh war, where, for example, the political objectives

00:47:14.920 --> 00:47:19.800
[Amit Varma]: were clearly different on the two borders, whereas at first on the Bangladesh side, there

00:47:19.800 --> 00:47:24.440
[Amit Varma]: were covert operations. And then when war actually began, the objective on the Bangladesh

00:47:24.440 --> 00:47:28.760
[Amit Varma]: side was we go in and we do whatever it takes. But the objective on the Pakistani side was

00:47:28.760 --> 00:47:33.480
[Amit Varma]: simply we hold the border, we are not marching to Lahore. So would this be an accurate example

00:47:33.480 --> 00:47:38.440
[Amit Varma]: of a political objective, which then needs to be communicated to the army, so it can

00:47:38.440 --> 00:47:43.320
[Amit Varma]: then plan accordingly. And it can go wrong if you just have bureaucrats in the defense

00:47:43.320 --> 00:47:44.760
[Amit Varma]: ministry directing operations.

00:47:44.760 --> 00:47:49.840
[Guest]: Yeah, I say bureaucrats, they don't direct operations. But the example that you gave,

00:47:49.840 --> 00:47:57.640
[Guest]: in fact, let me tell you that the Indian army was not tasked to actually capture Dhaka for

00:47:57.640 --> 00:48:02.960
[Guest]: that matter. Yeah, that happened afterwards. I have an episode with Srinath Raghav, where

00:48:02.960 --> 00:48:09.360
[Guest]: he describes that in detail. So it happened afterwards. But 71 was one of the places where

00:48:09.360 --> 00:48:15.760
[Guest]: there is sufficient guidance given to the armed forces. So they knew much more about

00:48:15.760 --> 00:48:24.240
[Guest]: what they could do. Let's take another example. And that is Operation Parakram, for that matter,

00:48:24.240 --> 00:48:30.720
[Guest]: where the guidance, what Mr. Vajpayee told the chiefs were, kuch karo, what exactly is

00:48:30.720 --> 00:48:37.880
[Guest]: to be done, was never given to them. So all they did was to mobilize. And then they put

00:48:37.880 --> 00:48:43.240
[Guest]: into action what they thought should be the next thing, which is to capture large parts

00:48:43.240 --> 00:48:49.520
[Guest]: of Pakistani territory, which is the norm, which they have been used to. Because there

00:48:49.520 --> 00:48:51.760
[Amit Varma]: was some political guidance given to that.

00:48:51.760 --> 00:48:54.480
[Amit Varma]: So there's no interaction there between the geopolitics and the military.

00:48:54.480 --> 00:49:00.320
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, so actually, the lack of clarity of what exactly had to be achieved, is what

00:49:00.320 --> 00:49:04.760
[Guest]: was the problem in Operation Parakram, and we know what happened. So this lesson is with

00:49:04.760 --> 00:49:13.080
[Guest]: us, historically, and so on, in every report that we need to have. So this has been identified.

00:49:13.080 --> 00:49:18.040
[Guest]: So that is why this Defense Planning Committee, which was in, I think, 2018, they have constituted

00:49:18.040 --> 00:49:24.440
[Guest]: one of the tasks which is given to them, is to come out with a national security strategy.

00:49:24.440 --> 00:49:29.800
[Guest]: It is not the case that there was no strategy before, that the National Security Advisory

00:49:29.800 --> 00:49:35.200
[Guest]: Board or the National Security Council Secretariat was instrumental in actually getting a strategy

00:49:35.200 --> 00:49:42.960
[Guest]: out, but it never found political acceptability. So we don't have it. I mean, so we are here,

00:49:42.960 --> 00:49:51.240
[Guest]: which actually now getting into geopolitical, let's say, turbulence, and we still lack a

00:49:51.240 --> 00:49:56.280
[Guest]: document, a mother document, which will guide the development of our armed forces.

00:49:56.280 --> 00:50:00.680
[Amit Varma]: So what would this national security strategy or this mother document as it were, what would

00:50:00.680 --> 00:50:05.960
[Amit Varma]: it then lay out? Would it sort of lay out geopolitical considerations that would limit

00:50:05.960 --> 00:50:11.120
[Amit Varma]: and guide your military actions? Like in the instance of Parakram, for example, would it

00:50:11.120 --> 00:50:15.280
[Amit Varma]: have laid out that yes, you can mobilize, but kindly do not invade, because we don't

00:50:15.280 --> 00:50:19.240
[Amit Varma]: know how they will respond. And it could be nuclear. And does it embed those kinds of

00:50:19.240 --> 00:50:20.240
[Guest]: things?

00:50:20.240 --> 00:50:25.160
[Guest]: No, no, no, not at all. This is about the type of military instrument you want to develop.

00:50:25.160 --> 00:50:30.600
[Guest]: What are the capabilities and the capacities that you want to have? One of the first meta

00:50:30.600 --> 00:50:36.120
[Guest]: questions which is required to be answered, and it has to come from political guidance.

00:50:36.120 --> 00:50:41.600
[Guest]: It has to be answered by the military, but it has to come from political guidance. What

00:50:41.600 --> 00:50:48.640
[Guest]: is the balance between continental and maritime power that we must have? How do we strike

00:50:48.640 --> 00:50:55.480
[Guest]: this balance? Should we put our efforts to become strong in the Indian Ocean, where we

00:50:55.480 --> 00:51:02.440
[Guest]: have the maximum potential, utilize it? Or should we be able to capture large parts of

00:51:02.440 --> 00:51:08.680
[Guest]: territory in Pakistan and in Tibet? These are choices that you have to make. Or do we

00:51:08.680 --> 00:51:15.560
[Guest]: defend in the north? And do we defend in the west? And then do we actually have more capability

00:51:15.560 --> 00:51:20.760
[Guest]: for projecting power in the oceans? These are choices, but these choices the military

00:51:20.760 --> 00:51:27.160
[Guest]: cannot make by itself. It has to come from a political guidance. That is what I'm talking

00:51:27.160 --> 00:51:33.160
[Guest]: about. You might call it a national security doctrine or a strategy. In the absence of

00:51:33.160 --> 00:51:39.080
[Guest]: that document is where we are having this problem, where we have our clarity. I mean,

00:51:39.080 --> 00:51:43.720
[Guest]: it will never be clear. We'll always actually have difficulty, because defense planning

00:51:43.720 --> 00:51:51.360
[Guest]: essentially is about trying to see balance your resources with the type of threats that

00:51:51.360 --> 00:52:00.720
[Guest]: you have. And the military, therefore, will have to plan not what it wants to do, what

00:52:00.720 --> 00:52:06.000
[Guest]: it can do with the resources that is likely to be made of it. So even on that front, it

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:11.280
[Guest]: has not been clear as to the type of budgets you can plan out. So that is another defense

00:52:11.280 --> 00:52:18.280
[Guest]: planning problem which has endured, has not been resolved as yet. And therefore, although

00:52:18.280 --> 00:52:23.080
[Guest]: a defense planning committee has been announced, we are not quite clear as to where they have

00:52:23.080 --> 00:52:29.200
[Guest]: reached and whether the situation has changed. But the essential problem still remains, which

00:52:29.200 --> 00:52:36.280
[Guest]: is the root of the problem, which is the lack of political guidance. In the absence of the

00:52:36.280 --> 00:52:41.520
[Guest]: political guidance, we have something which we call the defense minister's directive.

00:52:41.520 --> 00:52:49.040
[Guest]: That's a document which the defense minister gives three services on which they can plan.

00:52:49.040 --> 00:52:55.840
[Guest]: But the defense ministry does not have the type of expertise to, let's say, write this

00:52:55.840 --> 00:53:02.040
[Guest]: directive. So this directive is mostly written by the military itself, goes to the defense

00:53:02.040 --> 00:53:07.560
[Guest]: ministry, who then probably adds or minuses it and comes back to the same guys who've

00:53:07.560 --> 00:53:13.520
[Guest]: written it. So it's something which you have devised, and it's really certainly not what

00:53:13.520 --> 00:53:14.520
[Amit Varma]: you actually want.

00:53:14.520 --> 00:53:20.040
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, this again gets me to actually a question of economics, but not in the way

00:53:20.040 --> 00:53:24.120
[Amit Varma]: you'd expect. We'll take a quick commercial break. And when we come back, we'll continue

