[Amit Varma]: the Indian Army. And, you know, in all of this, you were just sort of talking about

00:54:52.680 --> 00:54:57.680
[Amit Varma]: how if there is a national security doctrine, then that sets the parameters within which

00:54:57.680 --> 00:55:02.160
[Amit Varma]: all the forces then have to act. Like, if you want to be a maritime power, then, you

00:55:02.160 --> 00:55:06.600
[Amit Varma]: know, the Navy needs to focus on particular things and be a particular size and so on

00:55:06.600 --> 00:55:11.920
[Amit Varma]: and so forth. My question to you is this, you know, that as someone who's into economics,

00:55:11.920 --> 00:55:16.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, when I look at, say, public choice theory, what public choice theory teaches

00:55:16.240 --> 00:55:21.920
[Amit Varma]: us is that you apply the tools of economics to look at how governments function. So, you

00:55:21.920 --> 00:55:25.720
[Amit Varma]: know, I look at politicians, I look at bureaucrats, and I'll say, what are their incentives? They

00:55:25.720 --> 00:55:29.960
[Amit Varma]: are human beings responding to a particular set of incentives. Let me carry that forward

00:55:29.960 --> 00:55:35.480
[Amit Varma]: now into the domain of the armed forces, that I would assume that just as a bureaucrat's

00:55:35.480 --> 00:55:42.000
[Amit Varma]: main incentives are to maximize his power and his budgets. Similarly, anybody in charge

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:47.720
[Amit Varma]: of, say, armored division or any kind of unit within the armed forces will want to increase

00:55:47.720 --> 00:55:54.080
[Amit Varma]: their own power and their budgets. How do those incentives sort of play out in practice?

00:55:54.080 --> 00:55:59.600
[Amit Varma]: Is there politicking within the armed forces to grab resources? And in the absence of a

00:55:59.600 --> 00:56:04.840
[Amit Varma]: national security doctrine, as you said, does it then become extremely ad hoc that, you

00:56:04.840 --> 00:56:08.800
[Amit Varma]: know, which division of the armed forces can lobby the best for higher budgets? And does

00:56:08.800 --> 00:56:14.200
[Amit Varma]: that then determine where the money goes rather than this kind of broader strategic thinking,

00:56:14.200 --> 00:56:22.640
[Guest]: which is coming from? So, actually, as far as the within the army or the Navy or the

00:56:22.640 --> 00:56:29.840
[Guest]: Air Force, there'll always be different elements vying for what you call scarce resources.

00:56:29.840 --> 00:56:40.200
[Guest]: So that is natural in any case. But if that is guided by a budget and a prioritization

00:56:40.200 --> 00:56:47.080
[Guest]: of resources based on what is your capability that you want to develop, it has nothing to

00:56:47.080 --> 00:56:53.440
[Guest]: do with the individual parts as much as it has to do with the capability. So you have

00:56:53.440 --> 00:56:58.940
[Guest]: actually now a system by which you identify capabilities. You have a five-year capability

00:56:58.940 --> 00:57:06.160
[Guest]: development plan. And that capability development plan has to be firstly a military plan. Then

00:57:06.160 --> 00:57:12.520
[Guest]: it has to be converted as far as in this military, in this plan, what is the capability the Air

00:57:12.520 --> 00:57:17.240
[Guest]: Force needs to have? What the Navy needs to have? The army needs to have? Within the army,

00:57:17.240 --> 00:57:21.480
[Guest]: what are the elements within the army? So it goes down like that. So you have to first

00:57:21.480 --> 00:57:27.400
[Guest]: tackle the problem at the top, because unless you tackle the problem at the top, this thing

00:57:27.400 --> 00:57:33.480
[Guest]: will always be there, that the guys down below will always be asking for more and trying

00:57:33.480 --> 00:57:38.120
[Guest]: to see as to how they can get more. So that is not where the problem is. We have to tackle

00:57:38.120 --> 00:57:45.240
[Guest]: the problem at which it is, from where it originates. And that problem is about, firstly,

00:57:45.240 --> 00:57:48.640
[Guest]: what is the type of budget? And this is a political decision. And it's sometimes bread

00:57:48.640 --> 00:57:55.800
[Guest]: versus butter debate. That's a political debate. How much actually of the public good are you

00:57:55.800 --> 00:58:01.620
[Guest]: actually going to invest for national security? I mean, that's just, it's a political decision.

00:58:01.620 --> 00:58:10.680
[Guest]: So if you look at the defense budget today, it's probably the lowest in terms of the GNP

00:58:10.680 --> 00:58:16.360
[Guest]: since 1962. And that budget actually also been severely constrained by the fact that

00:58:16.360 --> 00:58:21.960
[Guest]: defense pensions is also boomed. So you don't have enough money for maintaining and for

00:58:21.960 --> 00:58:28.080
[Guest]: capital acquisitions. So we have a budgetary problem right now. Combined with this budgetary

00:58:28.080 --> 00:58:34.120
[Guest]: problem, we have a problem of how do we prioritize depending upon, we are not very clear in terms

00:58:34.120 --> 00:58:40.040
[Guest]: of military capacity. We might be clear in terms of service specific capacities. You

00:58:40.040 --> 00:58:47.640
[Guest]: know, the Air Force wants to have long range bombers, the Navy wants to have submarines

00:58:47.640 --> 00:58:54.120
[Guest]: and so on. But the fact is that all this has to be measured finally, in terms of military

00:58:54.120 --> 00:58:55.120
[Amit Varma]: capacity.

00:58:55.120 --> 00:59:00.040
[Amit Varma]: First, how do all these parts fit into a whole which is military capacity? And B, how does

00:59:00.040 --> 00:59:04.920
[Amit Varma]: this military capacity then serve the nation's interests, which is the national security

00:59:04.920 --> 00:59:09.840
[Amit Varma]: doctrine, as you say? I'll come back to cost in a moment. But tell me this, it just strikes

00:59:09.840 --> 00:59:15.640
[Amit Varma]: me thinking aloud that there is also then a lag between geopolitical imperatives on

00:59:15.640 --> 00:59:21.200
[Amit Varma]: the one hand, and the building of military capacity towards that end on the other. You

00:59:21.200 --> 00:59:25.840
[Amit Varma]: know, in the rapidly changing geopolitical times that we live in, things change extremely

00:59:25.840 --> 00:59:32.160
[Amit Varma]: fast. And so a national security doctrine could presumably be revised constantly. But

00:59:32.160 --> 00:59:38.080
[Amit Varma]: to build military capacity towards any one end must be taking a huge amount of time.

00:59:38.080 --> 00:59:40.240
[Amit Varma]: You know, and how does that interplay?

00:59:40.240 --> 00:59:45.480
[Guest]: Yeah, let me just let me I'm not saying that the we have a national security doctrine and

00:59:45.480 --> 00:59:51.840
[Guest]: strategy, and that's the golden key. That's not going to be the case at all, because the

00:59:51.840 --> 01:00:01.520
[Guest]: national security doctrine itself would probably have to be constantly updated over a period

01:00:01.520 --> 01:00:09.240
[Guest]: of time to sort of catch up with what is a changing geopolitical situation. So this is

01:00:09.240 --> 01:00:16.040
[Guest]: not something you do once and it's over. It's constantly flowing. But it's in essence, in

01:00:16.040 --> 01:00:21.040
[Guest]: essence, you would have answered the mega questions, the meta questions, which you had

01:00:21.040 --> 01:00:27.640
[Guest]: to. That will probably not change. I think we must differentiate between the use of the

01:00:27.640 --> 01:00:35.480
[Guest]: instruments and the development of those instrumental capacities. That is an operational part, how

01:00:35.480 --> 01:00:42.040
[Guest]: it is applied. And that is sort of the that is not where India lacks by the application

01:00:42.040 --> 01:00:48.640
[Guest]: of those instruments. Where we are actually need for improvement is about identifying

01:00:48.640 --> 01:00:55.600
[Guest]: the type of capacities, matching them to the political objectives, and then prioritizing

01:00:55.600 --> 01:01:02.360
[Guest]: its development. That is where the area of improvement has to concentrate.

01:01:02.360 --> 01:01:07.520
[Amit Varma]: And is it the case that because you have the army, the navy, the air force and so on, with

01:01:07.520 --> 01:01:11.480
[Amit Varma]: all their, you know, their own interests to look after? Is it then the case that the armed

01:01:11.480 --> 01:01:16.760
[Amit Varma]: forces operate in these particular silos and they're not necessarily always pushing towards

01:01:16.760 --> 01:01:19.680
[Amit Varma]: the same end, but in a sense are almost in competition with each other?

01:01:19.680 --> 01:01:23.880
[Guest]: Yeah, I mean, this is, you know, there are three different geographies. So air force

01:01:23.880 --> 01:01:29.400
[Guest]: pilot looks at the world differently in the land. The army guy, the soldier on the ground

01:01:29.400 --> 01:01:36.680
[Guest]: looks at it differently. And so does the navy. And that is why the consciousness about bringing

01:01:36.680 --> 01:01:46.080
[Guest]: jointness and that's the word which is used where you need to have integrated organizations

01:01:46.080 --> 01:01:54.240
[Guest]: which can function together and the so that you can synergize the ability of the others.

01:01:54.240 --> 01:02:00.600
[Guest]: I mean, you, therefore, there's first requires to be an individual specific service specific

01:02:00.600 --> 01:02:06.760
[Guest]: capacity because only the air force can operate in that geography. And so is the army. But

01:02:06.760 --> 01:02:12.400
[Guest]: that is insufficient. We have to operate together. And today, bringing this together is what

01:02:12.400 --> 01:02:19.360
[Guest]: is called jointness. And that is, it's normally done by integrating it within the same structures.

01:02:19.360 --> 01:02:25.240
[Guest]: And that is why this is debate about integrated theater commands, which we don't have. And

01:02:25.240 --> 01:02:32.480
[Guest]: right now we've got about 17 commands. Each service has got different commands, geographically

01:02:32.480 --> 01:02:39.200
[Guest]: different located. And the good news is that the Department of Military Affairs has been

01:02:39.200 --> 01:02:47.320
[Guest]: mandated now in the new, this thing to bring about the integrated command. So we are well

01:02:47.320 --> 01:02:52.920
[Guest]: past the time of debate between the services. And the air force has always been an outlier

01:02:52.920 --> 01:02:58.480
[Guest]: in this saying that we don't require these integrated commands. But that time is now

01:02:58.480 --> 01:03:03.560
[Guest]: over because the political decision has been taken that there will be integrated commands

01:03:03.560 --> 01:03:09.440
[Guest]: and the CDS has been mandated to make that happen. So it is that's quite a lot of progress.

01:03:09.440 --> 01:03:14.120
[Amit Varma]: Let's kind of talk about something you alluded to earlier before the break, which is about

01:03:14.120 --> 01:03:18.920
[Amit Varma]: costs and budgets. I'll quote from a piece written by Sushant Singh in 2018, though it's

01:03:18.920 --> 01:03:24.840
[Amit Varma]: still relevant now, where he was talking about the different vice chiefs meeting a parliamentary

01:03:24.840 --> 01:03:31.000
[Amit Varma]: delegation. And here he quotes, quote, the army vice chief told the MPs that 68% of the

01:03:31.000 --> 01:03:35.600
[Amit Varma]: army's equipment is vintage, and the capital budget doesn't even cater for the committed

01:03:35.600 --> 01:03:41.640
[Amit Varma]: payments of 125 ongoing procurement deals. Leave alone provide funds to replace the vintage

01:03:41.640 --> 01:03:47.880
[Amit Varma]: equipment. There is no budget for making emergency procurements or for providing perimeter security

01:03:47.880 --> 01:03:53.160
[Amit Varma]: to army camps susceptible to terrorist attacks. The powers to buy ammunition and spares for

01:03:53.160 --> 01:03:58.040
[Amit Varma]: critical stocking levels needed for 10 days of war fighting have been delegated to the

01:03:58.040 --> 01:04:02.480
[Amit Varma]: defense services, but not enough funds have been allocated for it. On top of that, the

01:04:02.480 --> 01:04:07.920
[Amit Varma]: army will be saddled with an additional bill of 5000 crore due to increased taxes because

01:04:07.920 --> 01:04:13.440
[Amit Varma]: of GST. But no additional money has been made available for it. Besides paying salaries,

01:04:13.440 --> 01:04:18.880
[Amit Varma]: there is little else that the army will be able to do with the money given by the government.

01:04:18.880 --> 01:04:24.040
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote. And, you know, what I often hear from people is that forget the nuclear element

01:04:24.040 --> 01:04:28.160
[Amit Varma]: of it. If we were to fight a conventional war with Pakistan today, there is a chance

01:04:28.160 --> 01:04:33.120
[Amit Varma]: that we would lose because of under preparedness and because a lot of our equipment is so out

01:04:33.120 --> 01:04:39.640
[Amit Varma]: of date and so on. How true is that? I mean, should we be alarmed? Well, I think to say

01:04:39.640 --> 01:04:46.960
[Guest]: that we would lose to Pakistan and I mean, just the size of our country and the size

01:04:46.960 --> 01:04:52.920
[Guest]: of our armed forces itself is fundamentally defeatist and very pessimistic, I'm afraid

01:04:52.920 --> 01:04:57.840
[Guest]: and completely disagree with that. I guess people who say this do it to make a rhetorical

01:04:57.840 --> 01:05:02.680
[Guest]: point about. No, you don't. You don't fight. Let me tell you with money or you don't fight

01:05:02.680 --> 01:05:09.800
[Guest]: only with the equipment. You also fight. And that is the strongest with what you call the

01:05:09.800 --> 01:05:17.800
[Guest]: fighting spirit. So if the army itself feels and that's the point I make that you are you

01:05:17.800 --> 01:05:23.840
[Guest]: can't fight this guy because that guy is stronger. That means you have lost it before the fight

01:05:23.840 --> 01:05:28.000
[Amit Varma]: because that means you lost the spirit to fight. Let's assume fighting spirit is equal

01:05:28.000 --> 01:05:32.120
[Amit Varma]: on both sides because we should also give those guys some credit. Let's assume both

01:05:32.120 --> 01:05:37.600
[Guest]: sides have optimal fighting spirit. Yeah, but just the sheer size of the armed forces,

01:05:37.600 --> 01:05:42.760
[Guest]: the sheer size of the Air Force and the Navy and even the armed force.

01:05:42.760 --> 01:05:47.480
[Amit Varma]: Okay, leave aside this rhetorical point that I cited. But in general, do we have a problem

01:05:47.480 --> 01:05:55.560
[Amit Varma]: in terms of how our equipment like Sushant pointed out more than 60% is vintage equipment?

01:05:55.560 --> 01:05:59.200
[Amit Varma]: And do we have a problem with modernizing the armed forces?

01:05:59.200 --> 01:06:04.480
[Guest]: Yes, that is what I know. I'm very, very aware of what the Vice Chief told the Parliamentary

01:06:04.480 --> 01:06:09.000
[Guest]: Committee and so on. And he actually laid it bare, saying that these are all the problems

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:15.120
[Guest]: and he's quite right. Let's not forget that as far as budgets are concerned, this is probably

01:06:15.120 --> 01:06:20.280
[Guest]: the lowest we have reached since 1962 war. So there is an issue with the budget. And

01:06:20.280 --> 01:06:23.560
[Guest]: the fact that the budgets have remained where it is.

01:06:23.560 --> 01:06:25.680
[Amit Varma]: When you say lowest, you mean as percentage of GDP?

01:06:25.680 --> 01:06:30.040
[Guest]: As percentage of GDP, which means you can actually afford, you could afford much more

01:06:30.040 --> 01:06:36.240
[Guest]: earlier now you're going to have much less. The point is, the equipment which we have

01:06:36.240 --> 01:06:43.880
[Guest]: right now is being constrained, not only by budgets, which is a certainty. And as I told

01:06:43.880 --> 01:06:51.080
[Guest]: you earlier, the defence pension is also another issue which is impinged on the budget. But

01:06:51.080 --> 01:07:04.760
[Guest]: also our capacity to design, develop, research, and produce defence equipment of our own has

01:07:04.760 --> 01:07:06.840
[Amit Varma]: remained practically stagnant.

01:07:06.840 --> 01:07:08.400
[Amit Varma]: Despite all the make in India rhetoric?

01:07:08.400 --> 01:07:12.800
[Guest]: We have had all these make in India and so on. But the fact is that we haven't moved.

01:07:12.800 --> 01:07:19.680
[Guest]: We still remain one of the largest arms importer in the world. It is also a strategic weakness.

01:07:19.680 --> 01:07:24.560
[Guest]: Because we have to buy from others and they can always give us stop spares if not anything

01:07:24.560 --> 01:07:35.160
[Guest]: else in times of crisis. This is the defence industrial base of the nation has not progressed

01:07:35.160 --> 01:07:41.520
[Guest]: to what it should be. And that remains the weakness. So we have a weakness of not being

01:07:41.520 --> 01:07:48.400
[Guest]: able to produce our own arms to our procurement system, which means that even if we don't

01:07:48.400 --> 01:07:54.440
[Guest]: produce, we want to buy it from outside, itself is so tedious, and so long, that it takes

01:07:54.440 --> 01:08:01.740
[Guest]: a long time to procure it from outside, from another, let's say, off the shelf. In combination,

01:08:01.740 --> 01:08:07.600
[Guest]: that means now you have a budget problem, which is going greater. And the fact that

01:08:07.600 --> 01:08:13.240
[Guest]: you can't produce anything, and it takes longer time to procure it from others. This is a

01:08:13.240 --> 01:08:19.160
[Guest]: deadly combination. So it is because of this combination that the Vice Chief of Army Staff

01:08:19.160 --> 01:08:24.440
[Guest]: had to now tell the Parliamentary Committee, this is what is our situation, and we need

01:08:24.440 --> 01:08:30.640
[Guest]: to do about it. And I'm sure after he made this statement, there probably was a lot of

01:08:30.640 --> 01:08:37.200
[Guest]: things which happened. It is not that we have not ever since 1999 Kargil War, which was

01:08:37.200 --> 01:08:45.720
[Guest]: the first major defence reform, which was attempted, studied and undertaken, and many

01:08:45.720 --> 01:08:55.400
[Guest]: other reforms are underway. The pace is what we must question. And that's been very slow.

01:08:55.400 --> 01:09:00.240
[Amit Varma]: What's the structural reason for that? Is it the bureaucratic nature of how decisions

01:09:00.240 --> 01:09:01.240
[Guest]: are taken?

01:09:01.240 --> 01:09:04.080
[Guest]: Yeah, well, actually, everybody's got to blame. You know, you have to say that this is only

01:09:04.080 --> 01:09:09.280
[Guest]: bureaucracy. I think it's unfair on the bureaucracy. Firstly, the major change, there will always

01:09:09.280 --> 01:09:14.120
[Guest]: be resistance to it. The only people who can get over that resistance, because there are

01:09:14.120 --> 01:09:19.560
[Guest]: interests within the institutions, let's say DRDO, within the military itself, within the

01:09:19.560 --> 01:09:26.480
[Guest]: bureaucracy, the only people who can get over that is actually the political leadership.

01:09:26.480 --> 01:09:32.800
[Guest]: And I think what they have done recently, which was the creation of the CDS, and the

01:09:32.800 --> 01:09:39.280
[Guest]: creation of the Department of Military Affairs, is something which is commendable from that

01:09:39.280 --> 01:09:48.160
[Guest]: point of view. Now, these are two changes which were needed badly. People had actually

01:09:48.160 --> 01:09:54.080
[Guest]: given up that this is ever going to happen. Now it's at least happened. But of course,

01:09:54.080 --> 01:10:00.080
[Guest]: everything will depend on the human agency, which will take it forward. But at least the

01:10:00.080 --> 01:10:05.320
[Guest]: structural reform which has been done, I think, is in the right direction.

01:10:05.320 --> 01:10:11.440
[Amit Varma]: So you refer to how Kargil for you was a realization of things that were wrong within the system,

01:10:11.440 --> 01:10:16.120
[Amit Varma]: and that also set off various attempts to reform the armed services. Can you elaborate

01:10:16.120 --> 01:10:20.320
[Amit Varma]: a bit on that? Like what went wrong that led to a realization of weaknesses within? What

01:10:20.320 --> 01:10:25.240
[Amit Varma]: were those weaknesses then? And, you know, what has been attempted since?

01:10:25.240 --> 01:10:30.200
[Guest]: You know, K Subramaniam, who actually headed the Kargil Review Committee, actually makes

01:10:30.200 --> 01:10:37.280
[Guest]: the comment that so far, we've been generally moving along in a manner that we have been

01:10:37.280 --> 01:10:44.160
[Guest]: lucky that we have not been badly hurt. It's time that we woke up. These are not his exact

01:10:44.160 --> 01:10:51.320
[Guest]: words, but this is what he wrote in his report. And from that report came what is called the

01:10:51.320 --> 01:10:58.640
[Guest]: Group of Ministers report, in which they looked at internal security, looked at intelligence,

01:10:58.640 --> 01:11:06.480
[Guest]: looked at border management and defence. Defence was looked at by Arun Singh, the former Minister

01:11:06.480 --> 01:11:13.080
[Guest]: of Defence. You know, he is a man who had a particular interest in defence matters.

01:11:13.080 --> 01:11:19.040
[Guest]: And his report, the Group of Ministers on Defence, is the one which is suggested and

01:11:19.040 --> 01:11:24.280
[Guest]: the changes which we see today, including the CDS, of course, he had not suggested the

01:11:24.280 --> 01:11:30.160
[Guest]: department, which is an additional change, but most of the changes which we are seeing

01:11:30.160 --> 01:11:38.080
[Guest]: today is derived from that report of Arun Singh, which deals with defence. And he identified

01:11:38.080 --> 01:11:46.680
[Guest]: that without these structural changes, without actually changes in the budgeting process,

01:11:46.680 --> 01:11:52.120
[Guest]: all these have been identified. The report is actually available in the public domain

01:11:52.120 --> 01:11:58.120
[Guest]: in certain deletions which have been done for security. And we are still actually in

01:11:58.120 --> 01:12:03.600
[Guest]: the process with the CDS, at least the main defence, this thing has finally been implemented.

01:12:03.600 --> 01:12:11.320
[Guest]: But it has taken us 20 years to do it. That's a long time. After that, in fact, in 2012,

01:12:11.320 --> 01:12:19.240
[Guest]: when the government of the day decided that this Cargill, this GOM report, we had to go

01:12:19.240 --> 01:12:24.360
[Guest]: past it because, you know, there was no movement on it. That's why they had this Naresh Chandra

01:12:24.360 --> 01:12:29.000
[Guest]: Committee report, a committee which is there. It again gave its report. It was followed

01:12:29.000 --> 01:12:34.400
[Guest]: by another, this thing of the NDA government called the Sheketkar Committee in 2015. So

01:12:34.400 --> 01:12:41.960
[Guest]: on in 2012, 2015, they have all made various recommendations. But the problem has always

01:12:41.960 --> 01:12:53.240
[Guest]: been that you can easily implement recommendations which suit the institutional interests. To

01:12:53.240 --> 01:13:03.160
[Guest]: implement others, you require political will, which must be imposed, because otherwise people

01:13:03.160 --> 01:13:10.360
[Guest]: will either put it to the side, keep it away, delay it. And CDS actually is a very good

01:13:10.360 --> 01:13:16.640
[Guest]: example of that, that political will has been exercised. Because even until recently, the

01:13:16.640 --> 01:13:23.200
[Guest]: previous Air Force chief was very vehemently saying that we don't need the CDS and we don't

01:13:23.200 --> 01:13:29.720
[Guest]: need theatre commands. So nobody was listening. Now political will is what... So I think defence

01:13:29.720 --> 01:13:35.320
[Guest]: reform, and I'm just not talking only about higher defence organisations, even the one

01:13:35.320 --> 01:13:42.280
[Guest]: which has not been done, which is the thing about the research and development organisation

01:13:42.280 --> 01:13:48.520
[Guest]: or the defence production organisation, without political will, you can't make any change

01:13:48.520 --> 01:13:54.240
[Guest]: because you see there are labour force of nearly slightly under two lakhs. They've got

01:13:54.240 --> 01:14:00.800
[Guest]: ordinance factories, which are there. So anything which you do against this thing, they would

01:14:00.800 --> 01:14:09.800
[Guest]: probably threaten a strike. So that is another area which the previous governments have not

01:14:09.800 --> 01:14:15.720
[Guest]: touched and not been able to touch. And this government also has not been able to. Hopefully,

01:14:15.720 --> 01:14:21.480
[Guest]: it should now concentrate its energy on the ministry, on the Department of Defence Production

01:14:21.480 --> 01:14:28.760
[Guest]: and the DRDO. Because the other aspect, and not that it's not being done, is the fact

01:14:28.760 --> 01:14:35.120
[Guest]: that we have kept, for a long period in our history, we kept the private sector out of

01:14:35.120 --> 01:14:42.480
[Guest]: defence industry. Now, of course, that attitude has certainly changed. And today's paper itself

01:14:42.480 --> 01:14:51.280
[Guest]: actually, you know, there's this concept of strategic partnership and there you have L&T

01:14:51.280 --> 01:14:56.440
[Amit Varma]: and one public sector, which is the Mazagon. We're recording this on Jan 22, by the way.

01:14:56.440 --> 01:15:04.160
[Guest]: So there is some context for the listener, because you said today's newspaper. So, the

01:15:04.160 --> 01:15:12.720
[Guest]: Mazagon dockyard and the L&T had now been approved. And these two can now decide, team

01:15:12.720 --> 01:15:21.200
[Guest]: up with the OEM, the original equipment manufacturer. And I think five of them have also been approved

01:15:21.200 --> 01:15:28.680
[Guest]: from Russia, France, Germany, Spain, and I think one more country, France. So, you know,

01:15:28.680 --> 01:15:33.560
[Guest]: this is a new model. We know that that submarine will finally come into the water after it's

01:15:33.560 --> 01:15:39.120
[Guest]: been produced only probably slightly less than 10 years from now. But these are changes

01:15:39.120 --> 01:15:46.120
[Guest]: which have slowly taken place. So, it is not that we are now at a standstill, we are moving,

01:15:46.120 --> 01:15:54.240
[Guest]: but as the pace of change is what we have to question. But more than anything else,

01:15:54.240 --> 01:16:02.300
[Guest]: this is also combined with the fact that there is certainly a dearth of budget for building

01:16:02.300 --> 01:16:09.480
[Guest]: military capacity, or the type of capacity that you want. That there is no doubt. So,

01:16:09.480 --> 01:16:14.560
[Guest]: what will happen is, when you don't have money, you actually will have to delay it. It will

01:16:14.560 --> 01:16:19.600
[Guest]: cost you much more because of the delay. So, this is a political decision. So, we'll have

01:16:19.600 --> 01:16:27.080
[Guest]: to wait and see, at least for this year's defence budget, whether there will be a change

01:16:27.080 --> 01:16:33.440
[Guest]: in this or not. And my guess is, it's unlikely to be because the economy itself is in such

01:16:33.440 --> 01:16:37.720
[Guest]: a state. So, this is a political decision. The fact that the public good of national

01:16:37.720 --> 01:16:42.720
[Guest]: security will have to actually stay in a particular place. They probably will not allow it to

01:16:42.720 --> 01:16:50.200
[Guest]: deteriorate, but I don't think they can increase this. Therefore, when you have a budget constraint,

01:16:50.200 --> 01:16:55.520
[Guest]: and when you have constraints in your capacity, the armed forces are supposed to make that

01:16:55.520 --> 01:17:04.440
[Guest]: up by actually devising your operational strategies, which you can afford. You cannot keep crying

01:17:04.440 --> 01:17:12.880
[Guest]: for better equipment, better this thing. The only compensation is, then you decide to fight

01:17:12.880 --> 01:17:22.120
[Guest]: in a particular way. And that is what you call operational genius, which will overcome

01:17:22.120 --> 01:17:28.800
[Guest]: this lack. And that is why military leadership has a major role to play. They can't simply

01:17:28.800 --> 01:17:33.800
[Guest]: blame and say that we don't have this, we don't have that, therefore, we can't fight.

01:17:33.800 --> 01:17:41.720
[Guest]: The idea that technology is the determinant of victory has been disabused in modern war.

01:17:41.720 --> 01:17:46.120
[Guest]: And I think the fact that the Americans, the most powerful nations in the world, is being

01:17:46.120 --> 01:17:53.920
[Guest]: defeated by the Taliban, who actually just have an AK-47 or the IED, the lowest level

01:17:53.920 --> 01:18:01.520
[Guest]: of technology, just goes to prove the point. So, you have to change your operational concept,

01:18:01.520 --> 01:18:07.240
[Guest]: depending upon the equipment that you can afford. And you can't say that you can't fight

01:18:07.240 --> 01:18:09.120
[Guest]: because you don't have certain things.

01:18:09.120 --> 01:18:15.040
[Amit Varma]: This also then brings me to my next question that the decision makers, both within the

01:18:15.040 --> 01:18:20.040
[Amit Varma]: armed forces and within government and the bureaucracy who are deciding on the future

01:18:20.040 --> 01:18:25.120
[Amit Varma]: direction that the armed forces takes, are likely to be slightly older people in their

01:18:25.120 --> 01:18:30.720
[Amit Varma]: 40s or 50s or 60s, and so on and so forth. But technology moves fast, military thinking

01:18:30.720 --> 01:18:35.320
[Amit Varma]: moves very fast. Like what I am reminded of is, you, for example, mentioned the way the

01:18:35.320 --> 01:18:40.440
[Amit Varma]: Taliban fights, where equipment is not so relevant. And I remember reading this book

01:18:40.440 --> 01:18:45.920
[Amit Varma]: by Fred Kaplan called The Insurgents, where he talks about how within the US Army, it

01:18:45.920 --> 01:18:53.680
[Amit Varma]: took them decades after Vietnam, to understand the potency of that kind of asymmetrical guerrilla

01:18:53.680 --> 01:18:59.400
[Amit Varma]: warfare and how to deal with that. And they learned it so late, in fact, that, you know,

01:18:59.400 --> 01:19:04.080
[Amit Varma]: they made similar mistakes even when they invaded Iraq to begin with. And one of the

01:19:04.080 --> 01:19:09.040
[Amit Varma]: people he describes as carrying the new thinking forward was, of course, David Petraeus, who

01:19:09.040 --> 01:19:14.280
[Amit Varma]: then took over as the general and kind of changed course to make things work better.

01:19:14.280 --> 01:19:19.680
[Amit Varma]: But my question, therefore, is that the nature of modern warfare is changing completely.

01:19:19.680 --> 01:19:26.280
[Amit Varma]: And the cyber warfare, there is more mechanization, there's more AI being used. How much of an

01:19:26.280 --> 01:19:33.040
[Amit Varma]: issue is it that the decision makers who determine the future trajectory of the army may not

01:19:33.040 --> 01:19:38.720
[Amit Varma]: be entirely up to speed with the changes that are happening in both technology and strategic

01:19:38.720 --> 01:19:39.720
[Guest]: thinking?

01:19:39.720 --> 01:19:43.880
[Guest]: Yeah, obviously, there will be a lag between the people who are there on the top and the

01:19:43.880 --> 01:19:48.160
[Guest]: guys who actually understand what is the nature of the changes in technology. I mean, that

01:19:48.160 --> 01:19:54.200
[Guest]: is for sure. The question really is, I don't have to, as a military leader, understand

01:19:54.200 --> 01:19:59.360
[Guest]: their technology or how it works as much as what is the potential of its application.

01:19:59.360 --> 01:20:06.440
[Guest]: There is not something I understand how it works as much as what is it to be used for.

01:20:06.440 --> 01:20:10.760
[Guest]: That realization is what military leaders should have. And I think most militaries have

01:20:10.760 --> 01:20:18.040
[Guest]: now actually moved to that point where their military leaders have got this technical base

01:20:18.040 --> 01:20:23.880
[Guest]: from which will make this understanding easier. But this lag will always be there at the cutting

01:20:23.880 --> 01:20:30.440
[Guest]: edge where it's moving too fast for people who are a little older to actually be able

01:20:30.440 --> 01:20:35.040
[Guest]: to keep them up. So this lag, you cannot help. But that's institutionally, it has to be made

01:20:35.040 --> 01:20:41.160
[Guest]: up. You know, the fact that somebody down below will have to take it and show it to

01:20:41.160 --> 01:20:45.800
[Guest]: somebody else, convince him of it. And that always will be problematic because that guy

01:20:45.800 --> 01:20:48.780
[Guest]: may not be able to understand what this chap is talking about.

01:20:48.780 --> 01:20:53.800
[Guest]: So the point I want to make is, I am not for a moment saying that technology is not important.

01:20:53.800 --> 01:20:59.160
[Guest]: It is important. It's very important. And therefore, what I'm saying is, you can't always

01:20:59.160 --> 01:21:05.840
[Guest]: have cutting edge technology. That cannot be in everybody's position. But you have to

01:21:05.840 --> 01:21:15.800
[Guest]: fight with the technology that you have. And how you fight that is where your, let's say,

01:21:15.800 --> 01:21:22.120
[Guest]: your tactical brilliance comes about. How do you innovate? And that is where the human

01:21:22.120 --> 01:21:31.240
[Guest]: agency makes a difference. Because all technology will depend upon how it is going to be used.

01:21:31.240 --> 01:21:37.680
[Guest]: And that's where the human mind is much more important than the technology itself.

01:21:37.680 --> 01:21:42.920
[Amit Varma]: My question wasn't only about technology, though, but about strategic thinking as well.

01:21:42.920 --> 01:21:48.560
[Amit Varma]: For example, I'll, you know, ask a question in the context of the Indian Army, but in

01:21:48.560 --> 01:21:53.480
[Amit Varma]: context of what Kaplan's book is about and what counter-insurgency thinking has been

01:21:53.480 --> 01:21:57.960
[Amit Varma]: over the decades since David Galula wrote his classic piece on it. And the key thinking

01:21:57.960 --> 01:22:05.040
[Amit Varma]: there is that if you want to win in a battlefield like Vietnam, or like, say, Iraq, after you

01:22:05.040 --> 01:22:10.960
[Amit Varma]: invaded them, the way Kaplan breaks it up is he calls it 20% military, 80% political.

01:22:10.960 --> 01:22:14.720
[Amit Varma]: The key lesson that he points out is that you can't just go in and wipe out the first

01:22:14.720 --> 01:22:19.080
[Amit Varma]: bunch of insurgents and hold a particular piece of land if you're going to treat the

01:22:19.080 --> 01:22:23.400
[Amit Varma]: local population like shit and turn them all against you. So what you really need to do

01:22:23.400 --> 01:22:29.340
[Amit Varma]: is you also need to simultaneously having, you know, captured whichever city or part

01:22:29.340 --> 01:22:35.280
[Amit Varma]: of land that you want to capture, you simultaneously have to win over the local population, provide

01:22:35.280 --> 01:22:39.440
[Amit Varma]: them any governance that has gone missing because of your invasion, and so on and so

01:22:39.440 --> 01:22:43.840
[Amit Varma]: forth, which is a mistake that the Americans made when they first invaded Iraq, but that

01:22:43.840 --> 01:22:45.520
[Guest]: they later tried to rectify.

01:22:45.520 --> 01:22:49.360
[Guest]: The Americans have come to us for probably we would have told them this lesson because

01:22:49.360 --> 01:22:52.320
[Amit Varma]: this is one of the oldest lessons the Indian Army has carried.

01:22:52.320 --> 01:22:56.680
[Amit Varma]: But General Menon, not in Kashmir. The reason I would hold that we have lost Kashmir and

01:22:56.680 --> 01:23:01.320
[Amit Varma]: just yesterday we were offline discussing David Das's book, The Generation of Rage in

01:23:01.320 --> 01:23:06.240
[Amit Varma]: Kashmir, that what the Indian Army has actually done in Kashmir is entirely the opposite.

01:23:06.240 --> 01:23:11.600
[Guest]: Not true at all. Not true at all. In fact, what the Indian Army has done and the doctrine

01:23:11.600 --> 01:23:14.960
[Guest]: has said, the center of gravity is the people.

01:23:14.960 --> 01:23:17.760
[Amit Varma]: But in practice, we have treated them so badly.

01:23:17.760 --> 01:23:23.560
[Guest]: Not true. I completely disagree with that, that we have treated them badly. I don't think

01:23:23.560 --> 01:23:29.320
[Guest]: that is the case at all. You know, it's a uniform, depending upon the level of insurgency,

01:23:29.320 --> 01:23:36.320
[Guest]: the type of operations that you carried out, people will be affected. But I think the consciousness

01:23:36.320 --> 01:23:42.360
[Guest]: that this is all about winning the loyalty of the people is ingrained into Indian Army's

01:23:42.360 --> 01:23:48.800
[Guest]: doctrine for, I don't know, ever since we actually started using the army in the Northeast.

01:23:48.800 --> 01:23:56.080
[Guest]: So that has not changed. And let us not forget that when you do this over a time period,

01:23:56.080 --> 01:24:02.480
[Guest]: which we're talking about, there will be individual aberrations.

01:24:02.480 --> 01:24:09.880
[Guest]: In some cases, there might be, for very, very short periods of time, institutional aberrations.

01:24:09.880 --> 01:24:17.000
[Guest]: But let me tell you, as far as this issue is concerned, I think the Indian Army cannot

01:24:17.000 --> 01:24:22.920
[Guest]: be cast in the same light that you seem to cast it in. It would be completely unfair

01:24:22.920 --> 01:24:30.600
[Guest]: that the basic teaching, and I've served enough in Kashmir to make the point, I think we have

01:24:30.600 --> 01:24:37.080
[Guest]: been very sensitive to how to deal with the people. And we were always conscious that

01:24:37.080 --> 01:24:41.960
[Guest]: it is about the Kashmiris. They are the central cavity. It is their loyalty that we had to

01:24:41.960 --> 01:24:50.680
[Guest]: win. I think Indian Army should be proud of what it has done. And let us not take those,

01:24:50.680 --> 01:24:55.960
[Guest]: I'm not saying it's been perfect, those imperfections to say that is the norm. And I think that

01:24:55.960 --> 01:24:56.960
[Guest]: will be very unfair.

01:24:56.960 --> 01:25:01.480
[Amit Varma]: I'll defer to your experience there. And we can agree to disagree. And I wrote a column

01:25:01.480 --> 01:25:05.520
[Amit Varma]: on this, which I'll link from the show notes. But again, just thinking from an economic

01:25:05.520 --> 01:25:10.320
[Amit Varma]: point of view, we all know that people respond to incentives and power corrupts, which is

01:25:10.320 --> 01:25:15.040
[Amit Varma]: why, you know, one of the reasons that our army hasn't meddled much in politics is because

01:25:15.040 --> 01:25:18.480
[Amit Varma]: there are so many safeguards in place, and it doesn't have as much power as say the army

01:25:18.480 --> 01:25:23.840
[Amit Varma]: in Pakistan does. But equally, there are special conditions, for example, in Kashmir or in

01:25:23.840 --> 01:25:29.080
[Amit Varma]: the Northeast, where the army for large periods of time does have an enormous amount of power,

01:25:29.080 --> 01:25:34.600
[Amit Varma]: as much so if not much more than the civil administration over there, isn't it then inevitable

01:25:34.600 --> 01:25:40.080
[Amit Varma]: that those incentives will come into play and whatever your doctrine might actually

01:25:40.080 --> 01:25:44.360
[Amit Varma]: state, whatever the established wisdom within the army might be that treat the people well

01:25:44.360 --> 01:25:49.560
[Amit Varma]: in the hearts of the people, that what is happening on the ground is slightly different.

01:25:49.560 --> 01:25:52.440
[Amit Varma]: And of course, I'll defer to your experience in Kashmir. And you're absolutely right, that

01:25:52.440 --> 01:25:58.640
[Amit Varma]: is very easy to cherry pick a few things that have gone wrong and point to those as evidence

01:25:58.640 --> 01:26:03.320
[Amit Varma]: of something larger. But it does seem to me that one of the ways in which India has failed

01:26:03.320 --> 01:26:06.120
[Amit Varma]: is in winning the minds and hearts of Kashmiris.

01:26:06.120 --> 01:26:14.400
[Guest]: I don't think that the army has been, army might be the object today of their, let's

01:26:14.400 --> 01:26:20.600
[Guest]: say anger, because it's a symbol of the state. It is not because what the army has done to

01:26:20.600 --> 01:26:25.440
[Guest]: the people. So there is a difference here. And I think this difference is very important.

01:26:25.440 --> 01:26:32.400
[Guest]: I think for an army, which has actually spent nearly two decades continuously in a situation

01:26:32.400 --> 01:26:41.120
[Guest]: of violence, I think the performance has been commendable. It is not perfect and I'm not

01:26:41.120 --> 01:26:48.680
[Guest]: claiming perfection at all. But if you really look at it from the point of view of what

01:26:48.680 --> 01:26:53.400
[Guest]: was achieved, after all, where we are now and where we were, let's say during this 20

01:26:53.400 --> 01:27:00.480
[Guest]: years, we've been in different points in time, we've gone through ups and downs, you know.

01:27:00.480 --> 01:27:06.000
[Guest]: But it has nothing to do with what the army has done. In fact, whenever the army, the

01:27:06.000 --> 01:27:13.400
[Guest]: only main aim is to keep violence under controllable levels, so that the political process can

01:27:13.400 --> 01:27:20.240
[Guest]: resolve it. What we have failed in Kashmir is not about the army's performance. It's

01:27:20.240 --> 01:27:26.040
[Guest]: a political process that even when violence levels were down, the political process was

01:27:26.040 --> 01:27:34.120
[Guest]: not put into effect. So I think I would not agree that the army is a cause of the problem

01:27:34.120 --> 01:27:39.720
[Guest]: there. Definitely not the case. Army is an instrument of the state and therefore people

01:27:39.720 --> 01:27:45.240
[Guest]: view it as a symbol of the state. So today if they're angry against the state, then obviously

01:27:45.240 --> 01:27:49.840
[Guest]: that anger will be direct to the army. Not because what the army is doing, because it

01:27:49.840 --> 01:27:55.640
[Guest]: is part of this state. So I think, you know, I completely disagree with what the notion

01:27:55.640 --> 01:28:02.040
[Guest]: that you have that the army has done. In fact, the human rights violations of the army for

01:28:02.040 --> 01:28:07.280
[Guest]: such a large force, if you really look at it in percentage terms, anywhere in the world,

01:28:07.280 --> 01:28:11.520
[Guest]: we would still come up on top. That's a fact, just in numerical terms.

01:28:11.520 --> 01:28:16.360
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough. Let's kind of move on to a topic where we would both be on the same page and

01:28:16.360 --> 01:28:20.720
[Amit Varma]: both equally concerned, which is about the politicization of the army. Now, one of the

01:28:20.720 --> 01:28:25.760
[Amit Varma]: refreshing things from what I can see is that so far the army in India, like you pointed

01:28:25.760 --> 01:28:30.560
[Amit Varma]: out, has stayed away from politics, has not been politicized. Is there a chance of that

01:28:30.560 --> 01:28:34.760
[Amit Varma]: changing over a period of time? Is there something that gives you cause for concern?

01:28:34.760 --> 01:28:41.360
[Guest]: Well, I think the chance of that changing can never be ruled out because anything is

01:28:41.360 --> 01:28:50.120
[Guest]: possible from that point of view. Institutionally, the army is well, very sensitive to the fact

01:28:50.120 --> 01:29:01.120
[Guest]: that it must maintain its political stance, culture. I think we must not take individuals

01:29:01.120 --> 01:29:08.080
[Guest]: as symbolic of institutional change because institutional change takes a much longer period

01:29:08.080 --> 01:29:14.560
[Guest]: of time. We might have a leader here and there who might make a political statement and then

01:29:14.560 --> 01:29:20.920
[Guest]: you can't say that the army is getting politicized, although we must always view it as dangerous

01:29:20.920 --> 01:29:29.040
[Guest]: signals and then it is for the institutions to make the correction. If it does not, then

01:29:29.040 --> 01:29:39.200
[Guest]: it encourages it. So, the danger will be more as time goes on, not less, because the Indian

01:29:39.200 --> 01:29:45.880
[Guest]: himself is getting to be more politically conscious. He's exposed social media and the

01:29:45.880 --> 01:29:52.600
[Guest]: rest of it, the information domain itself. The soldier, the officer cadre cannot be any

01:29:52.600 --> 01:30:01.280
[Guest]: different. So, the challenge of the institution is in that sort of milieu, how do you keep

01:30:01.280 --> 01:30:09.640
[Guest]: the body politic of the institution away from politics itself? And there's nothing better

01:30:09.640 --> 01:30:16.200
[Guest]: than the leadership being so conscious and not getting into or keeping away from political

01:30:16.200 --> 01:30:22.000
[Guest]: controversies, especially making statements which are loaded politically. They might not

01:30:22.000 --> 01:30:27.920
[Guest]: mean it, but the fact is that it's got a political load which can therefore the media can run

01:30:27.920 --> 01:30:33.080
[Guest]: with and so on. I think there is need for this consciousness and it is not now, it is

01:30:33.080 --> 01:30:38.800
[Guest]: always there. But today it is much more sensitive because you're actually, it's like you're

01:30:38.800 --> 01:30:44.480
[Guest]: on the stage all the time and people are looking at you. So, it's a sports arena where the

01:30:44.480 --> 01:30:49.040
[Guest]: game is being played and there's a whole lot of people looking at you. So, this consciousness

01:30:49.040 --> 01:30:53.080
[Amit Varma]: definitely have to be part of the military leadership. So, what has been the level of

01:30:53.080 --> 01:30:58.260
[Amit Varma]: autonomy that the army has to, for example, when it comes to things like the appointment

01:30:58.260 --> 01:31:04.360
[Amit Varma]: of generals and now the appointment of the CDS? And is that a sphere where the political

01:31:04.360 --> 01:31:10.180
[Amit Varma]: process has played a part in terms of, you know, how are generals selected and can political

01:31:10.180 --> 01:31:18.400
[Guest]: interference make a difference, sir? Well, the system is that beyond the particular rank,

01:31:18.400 --> 01:31:23.880
[Guest]: let's say a lieutenant generals, and let's say you want to appoint a CNC or appoint a

01:31:23.880 --> 01:31:29.160
[Guest]: chief, then you send a panel. And from the panel, the politician actually selects. So,

01:31:29.160 --> 01:31:35.640
[Guest]: this is therefore, and I think the system is absolutely correct. They should be able

01:31:35.640 --> 01:31:42.520
[Guest]: to select who they want. The panel is by seniority? The panel is by seniority and eligibility

01:31:42.520 --> 01:31:47.080
[Guest]: and obviously by seniority. You know, seniority is one issue which you can't totally discard

01:31:47.080 --> 01:31:52.200
[Guest]: in a hierarchical organization like the military. I mean, just to go on a tangent, like in the

01:31:52.200 --> 01:31:56.880
[Amit Varma]: IAS, what often happens is your initial rank when you're 21 and your initial rank in the

01:31:56.880 --> 01:32:01.200
[Amit Varma]: civil services examination will basically determine the order for the rest of the career

01:32:01.200 --> 01:32:05.960
[Amit Varma]: when you become cabinet secretary and so on, except in very rare circumstances. Is it like

01:32:05.960 --> 01:32:10.080
[Amit Varma]: that in the army or do you constantly have evaluations as you move through the ranks?

01:32:10.080 --> 01:32:14.720
[Guest]: It's the same. Actually, the order of your passing out from where you are, in what rank

01:32:14.720 --> 01:32:19.240
[Guest]: have you passed out will determine your seniority and it will remain that till the time you

01:32:19.240 --> 01:32:25.280
[Guest]: are, unless you miss a promotion board and you drop and join the next bank. So, that

01:32:25.280 --> 01:32:30.160
[Guest]: system is the same. See, I think the politicians should be able to choose the highest ranks

01:32:30.160 --> 01:32:35.480
[Guest]: of the military because that's a political choice. And I think the system is fair.

01:32:35.480 --> 01:32:36.800
[Guest]: Has it always been that way?

01:32:36.800 --> 01:32:43.400
[Guest]: It's always been that way. But the practice generally has been that you go by seniority

01:32:43.400 --> 01:32:49.160
[Guest]: on the thing that this guy has already reached that place. All of them are good, but there's

01:32:49.160 --> 01:32:56.840
[Guest]: nothing wrong about not keeping to that seniority. And I think this government has a lot of violated

01:32:56.840 --> 01:33:02.760
[Guest]: the norm, changed the norm, not violated, changed the norm in the sense that there are,

01:33:02.760 --> 01:33:08.120
[Guest]: we see now more cases where they do not always select the senior most senior.

01:33:08.120 --> 01:33:09.720
[Guest]: Like General Raworth, for example.

01:33:09.720 --> 01:33:16.040
[Guest]: Yeah, he was actually one of the examples. And even the President Air Chief in the recent

01:33:16.040 --> 01:33:23.680
[Guest]: instance is also the case. So, but I think that's a political choice and I think politicians

01:33:23.680 --> 01:33:28.360
[Guest]: have the right to choose who the military leader should be. So, that's not. But the

01:33:28.360 --> 01:33:39.320
[Guest]: politicization which you are actually referring to is whether the leadership is able to ensure

01:33:39.320 --> 01:33:53.520
[Guest]: that the institution they command is not used for political purposes, which is meant for

01:33:53.520 --> 01:33:59.040
[Guest]: party interests. I think that is where the differentiation is. You know, all the time,

01:33:59.040 --> 01:34:02.760
[Guest]: the armed forces is a political instrument, is the instrument of the state, can be used

01:34:02.760 --> 01:34:09.640
[Guest]: externally, it can be used internally. The question of politicization, which is now germane,

01:34:09.640 --> 01:34:18.760
[Guest]: is whether it is being used to benefit the party and not the state. That is, I think,

01:34:18.760 --> 01:34:25.800
[Guest]: where the differentiation comes. And that's when the leadership will have to take a call

01:34:25.800 --> 01:34:31.080
[Guest]: or have a dialogue with the leaders who are actually, if they have to carry out something.

01:34:31.080 --> 01:34:35.840
[Guest]: But that's all things which are done normally behind doors. We don't know what the type

01:34:35.840 --> 01:34:40.640
[Guest]: of conversations which are taking place. And, you know, it might be taking place. We don't

01:34:40.640 --> 01:34:45.160
[Guest]: know whether it's taking place or not, but it might be. So, I think we need to differentiate.

01:34:45.160 --> 01:34:51.520
[Guest]: What we have to watch out for is this difference, that it is not being used for the benefit

01:34:51.520 --> 01:34:56.960
[Guest]: of a party. As long as it is used for benefit of a state of the nation, it's probably okay.

01:34:56.960 --> 01:35:01.360
[Amit Varma]: So let's take a completely hypothetical example. And mind you, it's completely hypothetical.

01:35:01.360 --> 01:35:05.640
[Amit Varma]: Let us say that there is a party in power, which puts party above the nation. And at

01:35:05.640 --> 01:35:10.000
[Amit Varma]: a particular point in time, maybe responding to a terrorist act, they want to do something

01:35:10.000 --> 01:35:14.440
[Amit Varma]: macho for the sake of political optics. And they give the army order that, okay, let's

01:35:14.440 --> 01:35:18.220
[Amit Varma]: just carry out what we will call a surgical strike. But basically, you will bomb a bunch

01:35:18.220 --> 01:35:22.040
[Amit Varma]: of trees and nobody will be hurt. But this is what we need you to do for the sake of

01:35:22.040 --> 01:35:29.920
[Amit Varma]: optics. What is military ethics in this situation? Like, as an officer, are you therefore, as

01:35:29.920 --> 01:35:34.760
[Amit Varma]: a general, are you therefore bound to follow the orders of your, say, the defense minister

01:35:34.760 --> 01:35:39.880
[Amit Varma]: in this case? Or at some point, is there some point where you feel you would be duty bound

01:35:39.880 --> 01:35:43.600
[Amit Varma]: to put your foot down? And if you put your foot down, would it be only be behind closed

01:35:43.600 --> 01:35:48.320
[Amit Varma]: doors, after which you go ahead anyway, reluctantly? How does it all play out? I mean, and again,

01:35:48.320 --> 01:35:51.880
[Amit Varma]: I'm thinking aloud is the first time I've thought of such a situation. So, it has to

01:35:51.880 --> 01:35:56.520
[Amit Varma]: be a dilemma for a person within the army, which thankfully, perhaps, in our 70 something

01:35:56.520 --> 01:36:01.200
[Amit Varma]: years, we haven't faced it. But we could face in the future, who knows?

01:36:01.200 --> 01:36:08.240
[Guest]: I know, this is hypothetical, the exact problem of what is the legal part of this? There are

01:36:08.240 --> 01:36:12.440
[Guest]: two issues. One is a legal issue, which you're talking about. One is an ethical issue. Legally,

01:36:12.440 --> 01:36:18.240
[Guest]: the government is well within its rights to give the order, and they could actually justify

01:36:18.240 --> 01:36:25.120
[Guest]: it for whatever. I mean, they don't have a say for party. That is a concealed intent.

01:36:25.120 --> 01:36:29.760
[Amit Varma]: You can justify it for national purpose. You can always justify it for national purpose.

01:36:29.760 --> 01:36:34.280
[Guest]: So, the legal part is not what we are talking about here. We're talking about the ethical

01:36:34.280 --> 01:36:40.600
[Guest]: part. And the ethical part can only actually come to something through a discussion between

01:36:40.600 --> 01:36:45.760
[Guest]: the leaders themselves. And that is why this dialogue has to be constant. That if I feel

01:36:45.760 --> 01:36:50.440
[Guest]: something, I might, you can still overrule me. But the fact is that I should be able

01:36:50.440 --> 01:36:55.320
[Guest]: to express and say it. Or you can actually, you can take a decision yourself, which you

01:36:55.320 --> 01:37:02.200
[Guest]: think is the most important value that you have. But if the order is legal, the issue

01:37:02.200 --> 01:37:07.920
[Guest]: is they can't possibly disobey it. But you know, in the real world, you can actually

01:37:07.920 --> 01:37:13.120
[Guest]: obey orders and still disobey it. You can do so many things. So, it's all up to you.

01:37:13.120 --> 01:37:20.240
[Guest]: But the fact is that ethical disagreements will have to be dialogued.

01:37:20.240 --> 01:37:24.040
[Amit Varma]: Which is very complicated. Like, for example, going back to Nazi Germany, for example, which

01:37:24.040 --> 01:37:29.200
[Amit Varma]: has no relation to present times, let me clarify. But going back to Nazi Germany, if Hitler

01:37:29.200 --> 01:37:32.760
[Amit Varma]: gives you order to one of his generals, right, okay, this is what you have to do, you know,

01:37:32.760 --> 01:37:36.800
[Amit Varma]: run Auschwitz for me. There's no dialogue there. It just becomes an ethical.

01:37:36.800 --> 01:37:42.360
[Guest]: Yeah, so that's what it is. So, you as an individual, you can say that, I'm sorry,

01:37:42.360 --> 01:37:47.600
[Guest]: I'm leaving, you find somebody else to do it. I mean, that's what military leaders have

01:37:47.600 --> 01:37:48.600
[Amit Varma]: normally done.

01:37:48.600 --> 01:37:49.600
[Guest]: Have done in the past.

01:37:49.600 --> 01:37:52.880
[Guest]: If they don't ethically agree with it, they find somebody else.

01:37:52.880 --> 01:37:58.480
[Amit Varma]: Fair enough. I also want to sort of turn the economic lens on politics again, as I tend

01:37:58.480 --> 01:38:02.240
[Amit Varma]: to do. And again, I'm just thinking aloud. And because I'm completely ignorant of the

01:38:02.240 --> 01:38:06.960
[Amit Varma]: subject, I'm probably unaware of other ways of doing this that have been discussed. But

01:38:06.960 --> 01:38:11.480
[Amit Varma]: when you're talking, for example, about the two possible systems of promotion, that one

01:38:11.480 --> 01:38:15.920
[Amit Varma]: is as in the IAS, perhaps you just go purely by seniority, and you have a norm that the

01:38:15.920 --> 01:38:21.160
[Amit Varma]: senior most guy gets a job. And the other might be that you put a bunch of names by

01:38:21.160 --> 01:38:26.380
[Amit Varma]: seniority in front of a panel and the politician decides. Now, I'm thinking of the incentives

01:38:26.380 --> 01:38:30.920
[Amit Varma]: in each case. If you go purely by seniority, and if your whole career is determined by

01:38:30.920 --> 01:38:36.600
[Amit Varma]: how you scored in that one exam when you were 20 or 21, then the incentive for every officer

01:38:36.600 --> 01:38:42.160
[Amit Varma]: is therefore not to try very hard to excel because it doesn't matter. Your rank determines

01:38:42.160 --> 01:38:43.160
[Amit Varma]: where you go.

01:38:43.160 --> 01:38:48.240
[Guest]: No, I think you got it. You got it slightly mixed up. You see, the seniority on which

01:38:48.240 --> 01:38:55.760
[Guest]: you pass out of the academy in the IAS or the military is the seniority in your batch.

01:38:55.760 --> 01:39:02.040
[Guest]: Every time that you have to be promoted, you have to go through a promotion board as the

01:39:02.040 --> 01:39:10.320
[Guest]: seniority calls it. But when you get promoted, in your batch, you will still maintain that

01:39:10.320 --> 01:39:16.880
[Guest]: seniority which you had when you entered the service. But you need to go through a board.

01:39:16.880 --> 01:39:23.680
[Guest]: So the first guy who's number one in my batch may not even have become, let's say, a brigadier

01:39:23.680 --> 01:39:26.640
[Guest]: because he hasn't passed the colonel to brigadier.

01:39:26.640 --> 01:39:33.760
[Amit Varma]: So when you get promoted, you're immediately above him, right? But I'm okay, so I got this

01:39:33.760 --> 01:39:37.840
[Amit Varma]: wrong. But this is how incentives would have worked if it was seniority alone, but it's

01:39:37.840 --> 01:39:42.740
[Amit Varma]: not so that's sorted. But the other incentives I'm worried about is that if the politician

01:39:42.740 --> 01:39:48.200
[Amit Varma]: makes a final call on who's going to be the general, then the incentives are towards politicization

01:39:48.200 --> 01:39:54.240
[Amit Varma]: because then whoever the contenders are in that panel, which are put before him, their

01:39:54.240 --> 01:39:59.520
[Amit Varma]: incentives are to be political towards the political party in charge because that increases

01:39:59.520 --> 01:40:03.480
[Amit Varma]: the chance of becoming general. Isn't that the case? I mean, that's the way the incentives

01:40:03.480 --> 01:40:04.480
[Amit Varma]: work.

01:40:04.480 --> 01:40:07.400
[Guest]: So I'm just absolutely right. I mean, this is these are human systems. So what you're

01:40:07.400 --> 01:40:14.000
[Guest]: saying is actually is this will be the natural tendency. So this is now up to the maturity

01:40:14.000 --> 01:40:19.400
[Guest]: of the political leaders to deal with this issue. You know, do they actually want people

01:40:19.400 --> 01:40:26.200
[Guest]: who they think are of their kind, or do they want good political leaders to lead armies

01:40:26.200 --> 01:40:32.160
[Guest]: into battle and win? So this is a political choice. And that is where the maturity of

01:40:32.160 --> 01:40:37.200
[Guest]: political leadership matters. So I think in after 70 years of independence, if you think

01:40:37.200 --> 01:40:42.200
[Guest]: that this choice is still not to be left to the politicians, I think it may not be fair.

01:40:42.200 --> 01:40:46.040
[Amit Varma]: No, I think it has to be left to the politicians. But are there other sort of systems which

01:40:46.040 --> 01:40:49.560
[Amit Varma]: ameliorate the way the incentive structure works here?

01:40:49.560 --> 01:40:59.120
[Guest]: No, it has to be a mix of two between merit, which is the thing, and seniority. Merit can

01:40:59.120 --> 01:41:07.760
[Guest]: only be judged at that level. It's a matter of what the politician sees is the right guy

01:41:07.760 --> 01:41:12.920
[Guest]: wants to command. And in a democracy, I think that is their right. They must be given the

01:41:12.920 --> 01:41:18.560
[Guest]: choice. And unless you give the choice, how is India going to actually mature as a democracy?

01:41:18.560 --> 01:41:23.320
[Guest]: If you're going to keep seniority as the principle of this thing, in which means you don't exercise

01:41:23.320 --> 01:41:29.480
[Guest]: your judgment, how is this democracy going to mature? Because they might go wrong somewhere.

01:41:29.480 --> 01:41:33.600
[Guest]: But unless you go wrong, how do you get to being right, at least mostly right?

01:41:33.600 --> 01:41:38.480
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, and getting mature politicians is up to the voters, which is you and me. So we

01:41:38.480 --> 01:41:43.160
[Amit Varma]: will blame anyone else for that. So you know, I've taken so much of your time that I think

01:41:43.160 --> 01:41:47.360
[Amit Varma]: that if you know, when you were a serving general, if someone actually took so much

01:41:47.360 --> 01:41:51.000
[Amit Varma]: of wasted so much of your time, you would probably have court martialed them. But I'll

01:41:51.000 --> 01:41:55.160
[Amit Varma]: ask you two final questions to end it with. One is a question on which we pretty much

01:41:55.160 --> 01:41:59.320
[Amit Varma]: devoted an episode the last time we met. But I think for the benefit of listeners who may

01:41:59.320 --> 01:42:04.560
[Amit Varma]: not have heard that yet, it's worth asking it again, which is how does being nuclear

01:42:04.560 --> 01:42:10.720
[Amit Varma]: affect India's army? Because we've basically got deterrence in the sense that, you know,

01:42:10.720 --> 01:42:15.760
[Amit Varma]: it almost equalizes India and Pakistan in a sense, because either can obliterate the

01:42:15.760 --> 01:42:20.320
[Amit Varma]: other. How does it sort of affect the role that the army plays?

01:42:20.320 --> 01:42:28.440
[Guest]: The role that the army plays is affected because nuclear weapons actually impact on the type

01:42:28.440 --> 01:42:35.920
[Guest]: of political objectives which you can achieve, which essentially means that this idea that

01:42:35.920 --> 01:42:42.040
[Guest]: you can go and capture large parts of territory, let's say in Pakistan, is the one which we

01:42:42.040 --> 01:42:48.240
[Guest]: must disabuse ourselves of, because that would require the quantum of force, which can bring

01:42:48.240 --> 01:42:56.840
[Guest]: nuclear weapons to play. So what nuclear weapons has done is driven the armed forces to fighting

01:42:56.840 --> 01:43:04.800
[Guest]: to a level in which only the utility of force is only where you can achieve political objectives

01:43:04.800 --> 01:43:10.640
[Guest]: of a limited nature, not that you can subjugate the enemy by defeating him.

01:43:10.640 --> 01:43:14.200
[Amit Varma]: We don't need to march to Lahore ever again, basically.

01:43:14.200 --> 01:43:19.760
[Guest]: That's what it would mean. Because before nuclear weapons, you could actually have that

01:43:19.760 --> 01:43:25.560
[Guest]: guy surrender. That's what we did. And then he will listen to your terms. Nuclear weapons,

01:43:25.560 --> 01:43:33.600
[Guest]: especially between nuclear powers, has changed that paradigm. So the utility of force is

01:43:33.600 --> 01:43:40.840
[Guest]: not about imposing your will as much as to affect its will. And that is where the difference

01:43:40.840 --> 01:43:49.440
[Guest]: is. So this is actually what it has changed is the utility of force in political terms.

01:43:49.440 --> 01:43:55.240
[Guest]: And because that has changed, it will impact how you actually fashion and apply and use

01:43:55.240 --> 01:43:57.080
[Guest]: your armed forces. That's what has changed.

01:43:57.080 --> 01:44:01.440
[Amit Varma]: Fascinating. And our episode on this was very interesting. And I also had an episode on

01:44:01.440 --> 01:44:05.200
[Amit Varma]: the nuclear dynamics between India and Pakistan with Srinath Raghavan. So that will also be

01:44:05.200 --> 01:44:09.480
[Amit Varma]: linked from the show notes. My final question, which will almost seem like a cliche to my

01:44:09.480 --> 01:44:13.560
[Amit Varma]: listeners because I ask it to all my guests in terms of whatever is the subject we're

01:44:13.560 --> 01:44:18.480
[Amit Varma]: discussing is that when you sort of look at the state of the Indian Army and how fast

01:44:18.480 --> 01:44:23.680
[Amit Varma]: or how slow reforms have happened and what the current thinking on it is both from within

01:44:23.680 --> 01:44:29.280
[Amit Varma]: and from outside from the political class, looking, say, forward into the next 20 years

01:44:29.280 --> 01:44:35.480
[Amit Varma]: where there'll be new geopolitical challenges and the whole military landscape will continue

01:44:35.480 --> 01:44:39.640
[Amit Varma]: shifting and changing. What gives you hope and what gives you despair?

01:44:39.640 --> 01:44:48.040
[Guest]: I think the hope is that there is greater realization for the need for reform. The despair

01:44:48.040 --> 01:44:55.760
[Guest]: is our inability, despite knowing what we have to do, we cannot get it done. And unless

01:44:55.760 --> 01:45:02.080
[Guest]: we improve that, it is not that India does not know the type of reforms it wants. We

01:45:02.080 --> 01:45:07.920
[Guest]: simply are not able to implement. And as I said, we can blame the military, we can make

01:45:07.920 --> 01:45:14.120
[Guest]: the bureaucracy. But I think especially in the major reforms are concerned, we must hold

01:45:14.120 --> 01:45:18.640
[Guest]: political leadership to account for that, because they are the ones which can make it

01:45:18.640 --> 01:45:23.240
[Guest]: happen, like with CDS and the Department of Military Affairs.

01:45:23.240 --> 01:45:25.400
[Amit Varma]: Which you feel is a big move forward.

01:45:25.400 --> 01:45:26.400
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

01:45:26.400 --> 01:45:29.120
[Amit Varma]: On that hopeful note, General Menon, thank you so much for coming on the show.

01:45:29.120 --> 01:45:33.440
[Guest]: Thank you so much, Amit. Always a pleasure.

